\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2717339 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 I was born in M
erthyr Tydfil in the Welsh mining valley, on 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\super\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 nd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
 May, 1926, which was the day after the General Strike began!  And the family folklore said it was snowing heavily the day I was born!  (LAUGHS)  And I grew up a typical sort of South Wales Valley boy\rquote s life.  I went to Carmarther (?? \endash 
 005) Grammar School, which was one of the big schools, in those days, in South Wales - that was at the time when there was a strong educational ethos.  I won an Open Scholarship to Aberystwyth, which I had to win
, because this was before the 1944 Education Act, I couldn\rquote t have gone to University if it hadn\rquote t been for that.  And after I\rquote d been in Aberystwyth a year, I then went into the Army, because the War was on \endash  it was 1943 
\endash  and joined the Indian Army.  And my time in the Indian Army gave me some interest, I think, in what would now be called \'93other cultures\'94
.  When I came out of the Army, I went back to Aberystwyth and finished my degree, and the degree was in Geography and Anthropology, and the Anthropology was taught by a man called Amlyn (?? \endash 
 014) Reece, who was Director of Extra-Mural Studies, and was a great influence on me.  And Amlyn asked me if I would do some research in the community, because he\rquote d organised a number of post-graduate students who\rquote d d
one studies of Welsh communities \endash  Tom Jones, he was \'85 had done Aberdaron, Emrys Jones had done Tregarar and so on \endash  these were published as a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Collection of Welsh Studies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , and I thought I would do an English village, which was a very radical thing to do.  So I \'85 my wife was a schoolteacher \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9074305 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 So do you mind if \'85
 we seem to be going on very fast.  So that gives me a very helpful sort of outline, but could we go back, then, first of all, can you say something about your family background?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9074305 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Yes.  My grandparents, my grandfather was a coal miner and steelworker.  My father died when I was very young, and my mother went into the Civil Service and became Manager of the Labour Exchange, which was remarkable \endash  I didn\rquote 
t realise, at the time, that it was quite remarkable for a woman to become a Manager of a Labour Exchange in the forties \endash  and moved around, so I was brought up by my grandparents, who were Welsh-speakin
g, so I grew up in a Welsh-speaking household.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9074305 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
So this was the steelmakers?  You said one of them was a steelworker.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Yes.  Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Well, he\rquote 
d started life as a coal miner, and then as he became older he couldn\rquote t \'85 he found the work too physically demanding, so he got a job in the steelworks in Merthyr, the Dalais (?? \endash  030) Works \endash 
 famous from the Industrial Revolution.  And typically of his \endash  they were Welsh Baptists \endash  typically of his generation, they placed a great v
alue on education, so they were determined that I should be properly educated.  I was, actually, a studious boy, I think.  And in those days, you sat the \'85
 what became the 11+, there was a Scholarship Exam, it was called, the Scholarship for getting to the Grammar School, and this was for the whole of the Borough of Merthyr Tydfil, and the results were published in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Merthyr Express}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  \endash  the local paper \endash 
 and I came third in the Borough, which was a source of great pride to my family!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 So w
ere they really very cultured people, would you say?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 No, they weren\rquote 
t.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 They weren\rquote 
t, no.  They \'85 they \'85 um \'85 we didn\rquote t have a wireless, didn\rquote t have a radio.  Their life centred around the Chapel.  But they realised that if I
 was not to become a coalminer or whatever, I had to learn something outside, and I do remember an incident \endash  I was actually talking about this the other day \endash 
 when I was, in the fifth form, I was working through, or the fourth form, Chapter 5, or Book 5, of Caesar\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Gallic War}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  \endash  translating it from Latin into English!  A terribly tedious thing to do!  And my grandmother looked over my shoulder and saw what I was doing, and she said, what is \'85
 what was I doing?  So I said this was what I was doing.  She read it, and she said, \'93Well, why are you doing this?\'94  You know, \'93This Caesar bloke\'94.  And I said, \'93Well, he was a soldier and he wrote very straightforward Latin, so it\rquote 
s relatively easy to translate because it\rquote s easy to understand\'94.  And a long pause, and she said, \'93That\rquote s interesting, because when we have preachers in the \'85 in the Chapel, some of them are very easy to understand, because they
\rquote re straightforward \endash  usually the great ones \endash  but as these young men out of theological college have these high-flo
wn which no one understands, but everybody pretends to, (LAUGHS) and I thought of the contrast between the straightforward Latin and the straightforward \'85\'94 it was that kind of household.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Yes.  Did they talk about ideas at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Well, if they did, they were sort of ideas to do with religious beliefs and so forth.  But essentially, it was \'85 it was more a general atmosphere of encouragement.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Mmm.  And you got your interest in music from that childhood?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Er, yes.  My
 mother had four sisters, and a brother.  The brother died when he was 19, of TB, and I was named after him, actually.  And one of the sisters sang in the local choir, had a beautiful contralto voice, and she would come and say, \'93We\rquote 
re doing the \'85 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Dream of Gerontius}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 \'94 or something, or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The Messiah}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  and so forth, and we would talk about it, and I went and did piano lessons, but I didn\rquote 
t like it very much, so I sort of dropped that.  Yes, it was a fairly typical Welsh industrial sort of family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 And how 
did they relate to the Labour Movement and the politics at the time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 They didn\rquote 
t actually, I don\rquote t think.  If they did, I wasn\rquote t aware of it.  I mean, we didn\rquote t discuss politics very much, although I\rquote m sure they certainly voted Labour, because Mer
thyr with Keir Hardie and so forth!  (LAUGHS)  It would never occur to them to vote Conservative \endash 
 if they voted at all.  They were relatively apolitical.  It was only when I went to the Drama School that politics started looming large, and there, I think one of the things that influenced us was that the Folkestone Boys\rquote 
 Grammar School was evacuated to Merthyr, and we had a system whereby the Folkestone boys were taught in the morning, and we were taught in the afternoon, in shifts, and then they gradually 
integrated.  So this was our first experience of the English, of whom we were extremely suspicious, and we regarded them as English, Conservative, middle-class, prosperous, and we were Welsh, Labour, or Liberal in some cases, not very well off, and workin
g-class, and we used to have arguments with them about politics, although during the War, of course, this certainly wasn\rquote 
t a time of much political discussion, and the Nazis were bad, and we were the sort of good!  (LAUGHS)  When I went to Aberystwyth, well, I was only there for a year before I went into the Army, that was \'85 and again, they had King\rquote 
s College, London, evacuated to Aberystwyth (LAUGHS), so the same kind of dichotomy between the English and Welsh, and endless debate \endash  not so much about politic
s and things, but about cultural differences.  We regarded the Welsh as being poetic and sort of emotional, and the English as being rather cold and not poetic and so forth.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
And you were the only child?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
I was the only child, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Yes.  And would you say that you were really closer to your grandmother or your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid9394196 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Oh, my grandmother, because my mother could only come home about once a month, so I would see her \'85 and she died relatively \'85 she died before my grandparents, actually, so \'85
 and then, of course, I was away for nearly five years in the Army, and she actually died while I was in the Army, so I wasn\rquote t at home when she died.  My grandparents lived on, they both lived into their eighties, and they were \'85 yes, I mean
, I regarded them as, essentially, my parents, I suppose, called them \'93Mum\'94 and \'93Dad\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Do you think that that gave you an interest in kinship, possibly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 I don\rquote 
t know about interest, it certainly \'85 I mean, I took for granted that people had kindred, and that you could identify them.  I remember that, on one occasion, two people turned up from Risolven (?? \endash  ph \endash 
 096), which is north of Swansea, and Risolven was a remote place, and when they turned u
p, they were explained to me as being second cousins of my mother, I think, and the links were established.  In great detail I was told how they were connected, and they would add to this by saying, \'93Well, of course, you know, so and so\rquote 
s married someone else\'94 and so on, and I assumed that everyone behaved like this, that everyone had this extended family, very extended family, and that you located people in terms of family.  And so the Welsh habit of asking people \'85
 the first question you ask someone, in South Wales, is where do they come from?  Right?  And having asked them where they come, you then try to establish \'85 you say, \'93Ah!  I\rquote ve got an uncle who lives in Risolven\'94
, something like this, and you then try to locate them in terms of your own kinship system in Risolven.  If they come from somewhere where you don\rquote 
t have kindred, you ask a different set of questions to try to locate them.  And I, I mean, this is how it was.  I had a map in my head, of the families scattered \endash  the Griffiths\rquote s and the Williams\rquote 
s scattered all over South Wales - and if you went to any of these places, you\rquote d be expected to call in, not to write in advance, but simply to call in and say, you know, \'93I\rquote m passing through\'94
.  And I found an example of this, an odd example of this, actually, a long time later.  I went to a conference in Brighton, on the NHS, and I was talking to a group of people, and one of them said, of me, \'93
Everybody in Wales either went to school with him\'94, right? \'93or worked for him, or was a relative of his\'94.  And I said, \'93Don\rquote t be silly!\'94  As I was saying that, someone came up and said, \'93
Hello, Bill.  Do you remember me?  (LAUGHS)  \'93I once worked for you\'94, and everybody roared with laughter!  And this was to do with this kind of Welsh networking, because Wales is a \'85
 is a small country, and I grew up being accustomed to friendship networks, work networks, kinship networks and so on.  And, of course, when I went to \'85 when I then went to Gosforth, I regarded myself as going to a foreign country, and when I got off t
he bus in Gosforth, there was absolutely \endash  I don\rquote t think I put this in the book, I\rquote m sure I didn\rquote t \endash  absolutely a beautiful example of this, which made me convinced I\rquote 
d come to the right place, because I got off the bus, and there was a woman coming down the road, on a white horse, and she stopped outside the shop \endash  Barnes\rquote s shop \endash  and Mr. Barnes came out and said \'85
 and actually touched his forehead, said, \'93Good Morning, Miss Keene\'94, and she said, \'93Good Morning, Barnes\'94, like \'85 (LAUGHS) \'85 you wouldn\rquote t do th
at in Merthyr!  (LAUGHS)  And she then gave him her order, and he wrote it down and said, \'93Yes, I\rquote ll bring it up this afternoon, Miss Keene\'94, and off she went.  And I discovered that Miss Keene was actually the Rector\rquote 
s daughter, and the Rector\rquote s daughter clearly belonged to a different social class from Mr. Barnes.  And I thought, \'93Here is the English class system in action!\'94  (LAUGHS)  And it \'85 it couldn\rquote 
t be more different from industrial South Wales, where there was a strong egalitarian ethos.  And, in 
fact, this evacuee business, one of the people I became very friendly with was a chap called Gerry Cass, whose father was the furniture manufacturer, and he was Jewish, and we used to play chess together.  He invited me to his house, and they were Orthodo
x
 Jews, and Gerry made it quite clear that this was an extremely unusual thing to happen, because non-Orthodox Jews never went to the house, and I was being sort of admitted as a kind of experiment.  And I found this quite extraordinary.  There was a world
 here that \'85 so there must have been something, I suppose, in my \'85
 in the way I grew up, that made me conscious of social differences and kinship networks and things like this.  But it was really Alwyn Reece that opened my eyes to all this entirely new worl
d, because in Aberystwyth, I mean, the people were like me, they were working-class boys and girls \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
But before we get to Aberystwyth, do you want to say anything about the School?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
The School, itself - there were three schools, at that time, in South Wales, there were three schools that were regarded as the leading grammar schools.  There was Carmarther, the one I went to;  there was Barrygran (?? \endash 
 145) School;  and there was one in Cardiff \'85 er \'85
 Howard Gardens I think it was called, and there was intense competition between these schools, for Scholarships and things like this.  And the School was very academic, extremely academic, and placed a lot of emphasis on academic excellence
.  And when I won an Open Scholarship, at the same time a boy called Gwyn Williams \endash  Gwynalf (?? \endash  150) Williams \endash 
 became a very distinguished historian - also won a Scholarship, and another boy, called Hywel Davies, won a Scholarship to Oxford.  And this 
was such an event in the life of the School that the School was given a half-day holiday, which made us enormously popular!  But it was a very old-fashioned Welsh Grammar School sort of education, which \'85
 with, what I think must have been fairly high standards, and I think it was reflected in one way of \'85 epitomised it, was that \'85 in the sixth form \endash  remember this was 19 \'85 early 1940s \endash 
 in the sixth form, I think there were a dozen of us, the sixth form boys, and the girls were upstairs.  And of the dozen, I think ten became university teachers \'85 out of the 12.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 That\rquote s amazing!

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
And quite a few of them became professors as well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Extraordinary, yes.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Yes.  Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Were there any teachers who were particularly influential?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Er \'85
 I did English, History and Geography for what was called \'93Higher\'94 in those days, and the history teacher, I suppose, was.  He was influential, I suppose.  But no, there weren\rquote t \'85 it\rquote 
s only when I went to Aberystwyth that I met people I thought were great teachers.  At school, they were simply very competent, hardworking and \'85 I suppose, in some ways, very orthodox in what they taught.  So no, there wasn\rquote 
t that kind of influence, at all, in the Grammar School, that\rquote s the sort of place it was, and the sixth form saw itself as academic sort of fast track sort of people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
So perhaps we should move to Aberystwyth?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Aberystwyth, right.  Well, I went to Aberystwyth and read the \'85 the English Department tried to persuade me to read English, because \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Sorry, what did you do in the sixth form at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
I did English, History and Geography.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Because I was \'85
 and I hadn\rquote t realised it, but in the Scholarship Exam, my \'85 the paper that got me the Schola
rship was the English paper, so when I went to Aberystwyth, they tried to persuade me to do Honours English, because they thought I had a talent.  But I didn\rquote t want to do Honours English, I didn\rquote 
t want to do English, because I thought that bisecting the texts and so on was a fairly arid exercise.  So although I had to do it for the first year \endash  you had to do three subjects for the first year \endash  I didn\rquote 
t want to go in to the Honours School of English.  And in geography, the reason I chose geography was that t
he Geography Department in Aberystwyth had this remarkable history and tradition.  The Department had been established by a man called Harold Fleur, who was a sort of human/social geographer/archaeologist, and Fleur was then succeeded by \endash 
 and he was as great man, he was regarded as a great man \endash  by an even more remarkable person, I suppose, and this was Darrell Ford (?? \endash 
 189), who was appointed, as an American, to the Chair in Aberystwyth, at the age of 26, unbelievable!  And he did a lot of archaeology a
round Aberystwyth.  It was unusual, in Aberystwyth, to become Professor of Social Anthropology in UCL, where he did a lot of distinguished work in \'85
 in Africa.  So there was kind of tradition of geography and anthropology all mixed up.  And Fleur was replaced by a man called Emrys Bowen (?? \endash  194), who was a historical geographer, interested in \'85
 early Middle Ages and Dark Ages in Wales.  And Emrys was an inspired teacher.  Absolutely inspired.  Held us all spellbound.  And when I say \'93us\'94 \'85 when I came bac
k from the Army, I mean, the class there consisted of a fairly hard-bitten group of people who\rquote d all been in the War and so on, and Emrys would \'85 he was just a spell-binder.  So I thought, \'93This is what I want to do\'94
.  So I did geography, and \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 So
 what kind of geography was he teaching, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
He was teaching Historical Geography.  Well, it actually started with the \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85
.ithic!  (LAUGHS)  It was historical in the very deep sense.  And the first term was entirely pre-history, with a kind of geographical twist, as it were.  And \'85 but they \'85 they offered \'85 the course that was offered was a course called, \'93
The Anthropology of Advanced Societies\'94, by Alwyn Reece (?? \endash 
 210), who was the Director of Extra-Mural Studies.  So I decided to do this.  And six of us, I think did it.  And I lost interest in traditional geography because this was, I thought this is what I wanted to do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 So this was in your 
\'85 that second course was in your first year or \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
This was in the second and third year.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Second and third years.  After you came back from the Army.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
After I came back from the Army.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 I see, yes.
  So can you describe him?  What sort of person he was?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Yes.  Alwyn was \'85
 um \'85 Welsh was his first language, and as the Director of Extra-Mural Studies, he spent a lot of his time lecturing outside the University.  And the way to describe it was, 
I suppose, the sort of books that he found interesting and important, and worth lecturing about, were things like, A.M. Foucault\rquote s (?? \endash  218) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Kinship}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , and Maud Ragman (?? \endash  219), and people in the Tinkers\rquote  Library (?? \endash  219), who wrote a mixture of some ph
ilosophy and ancient history and things like this.  But he\rquote d also read some Malinowsky, and he\rquote d read some Radcliffe-Brown, and he decided that it would be worth \endash  and I think he was one of the very early people who did this \endash 
 doing a sort of anthropologic
al study of a Welsh village, so he actually did the study of his own, and he imported this into the teaching.  So, I mean, it was a very good example of research informing teaching.  And he also had these Ph.D. students doing their studies.  So when he ta
lked about kinship, we would have something about the \'93\'85\'85\'85\'85.. (INAUDIBLE \endash  228) Cross-Cousin Marriage\'94, and things like this, side by side with the extended family in \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85
.., and how you would see basic principles applying to both of these.  And I just thought this was absolutely wonderful.  And, I mean, I did \'85 I think I did well in it, and this is why Alwyn was \'85
 well, difficult to describe.  A very reserved man, sort of suggested to me that I might want to do a Ph.D., and join his little group of com
munity studies people.  Well, the other thing that Alwyn did was, he introduced me to another strong influence in my life.  He suggested that I read Conrad Allen\rquote s (?? \endash  237) books \endash  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The Irish Countryman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  \endash  and family included in Ireland.  And I thought the
y were absolutely superb.  Absolutely superb!  And that led, then, to looking at other anthropological studies of modernish communities as well as the classical ones.  He\rquote s the sort of person that\rquote s a bit difficult to locate, I think, in 
\'85 I think in the p
resent day, because he was very much immersed in Welsh non-Conformity.  He was a Welsh Nationalist, and very interested in Welsh politics in that sense.  And he was a firm believer in education as a means of developing an egalitarian society.  So, I mean,
 he saw education as allowing people to make judgements about the kind of society in which they lived.  And he was enormously popular as an extra-mural teacher, and he gathered around him members of staff who were of the same kind, mainly \'85
 although he was, I think, from a rural background, most of the staff there were, again, from industrial South Wales \endash  former steelworkers who\rquote 
d gone to extra-mural classes, then gone and done the degree, and had become extra-mural teachers, and were completely embedded in the culture of the people they were talking to.  And, of course, I was like that myself.  I\rquote d \'85 I\rquote 
d never lived in England, apart from a few months in the Army before I went off to India, so I knew nothing about English society, but there was nothing in the \'85
 the course, except of an academic kind, that told us about what life in England was like.  I mean, the studies that we were looking at were studies of Welsh communities, so they were familiar with us.  And the question that it raised, which was an end
uring question, was, \'93How far can you study your own society and stand outside it and be objective?  How far can you \'85 be separate from it?\'94
  And when I went to Gosforth, actually, there was a nice example of this, because the first Sunday I was there, and
 walking down the village street, and the church service ended, and the men came out and crossed the road, they went into the pub.  Right?  For a drink.  And I thought this was absolutely astonishing!  Because, to begin with, the pubs weren\rquote 
t open on a Sun
day in Wales!  (LAUGHS)  Apart from the Labour Club, and the Conservative Club, and people who went to the Labour Club and the Conservative Club, on Sunday, were regarded as dissolute and irreligious and so forth, and there were these men crossing the roa
d!  So in great excitement, I wrote to Alwyn and told him about this.  And he wrote back and said, \'93
This tells me much more about your Sabbatarian upbringing than it does about the English rural life!  (LAUGHS)  And this was an advantage, because being able to see these things from a culture that \endash  all right, we shared a language \endash  but 
\'85 it was very very different, and how we emphasised this.  And I think, although it wasn\rquote t intentional, the course \'85 with it\rquote s sort of bias \'85 I mean, even the studies we\rquote d looked at \'85
 like Arensberg of Ireland, and Jimmy Littejohn on Scotland, were not English.  I mean, there weren\rquote t many.  I don\rquote t think there were any community studies of England at the time.  So that was helpful, I think.  And he had Parkinson\rquote 
s \'85 the other thing about it was, he had Parkinson\rquote s Disease, and trembled a lot, we hadn\rquote t realised it was \'85 and he was, I think, a sick man.  So not long after I finished, he retired.  And so we were lucky, I think, to \'85
 to find him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Did you make any important friends at Aberystwyth?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Well, Gwynalf Williams, we\rquote d gone from school together, and he was a sort of close friend of mine, and then he went off and did a Ph.D. in London, and I went to Cumberland.  No, there wasn\rquote t anyone else, I don\rquote 
t think.  I mean, there were people that I knew and were friendly with, but my university career made this more difficult, because when I left at the end of the first year, I went into the Army, and the generation of young men who were with m
e, also all became Bevin Boys, so they went to work down the mines.  Now, what the mechanism was for choosing them as Bevin Boys, and not choosing me as a Bevin Boy, I don\rquote 
t know, because two of them were actually sons of non-Conformist Ministers in rural Wales!  (LAUGHS)  Wouldn\rquote t know a coalmine, you know, until they saw one!  And they became Bevin Boys, whereas I didn\rquote 
t, and I went into the Welsh Guards, actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Were you Commissioned, actually?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
No.  I went into the Welsh Guards, and I hated it.  I absolutely hated it.  Because, for example, you weren\rquote t allowed to have any books or a newspaper, you weren\rquote 
t allowed any reading material.  What you were allowed was writing paper and envelopes, and if you \'85 if they found a book in your belongings, you were put on a charge, because this was \'85
 the Guards disciplined to ensure that you did exactly as you were told, and you did nothing for yourself.  And although I admired it, and I could see what it was about, I decided I had to get out.  So I \'85 I asked \'85
 this shows the naivety!  I asked for an interview with the Commanding Officer, and told him that I wanted to move to something like the Royal Engineers, Topographical Branch, or something more suited to my training.  And he said, \'93Once a Guards
man, always a Guardsman.  March about!\'94  (LAUGHS)  And when I came out, the Sergeant Major said, \'93The only way you\rquote ll get out of here is by becoming an officer\'94
.  So I applied to go to a Selection Board, and was chosen as an officer, as an officer cadet, and went to \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85 (INAUDIBLE \endash  319 \endash  Rooton??) in Kent, and while I was there, we had an interview from a colonel, \'85\'85\'85
\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85 (INAUDIBLE \endash  321), who came to interview us.  I went in, and he said, \'93Sit \'85\'94 \endash  I remember the interview very vividly \endash  \'93Sit down, my boy\'94.  He said, \'93How would you feel \'85\'94  He said, \'93
What do you do for sport?\'94  So I said, \'93Well, I play rugby\'94.  And he said, \'93How would you feel about playing rugby, say, with black men, or Indians?\'94  And so I said, \'93Well, as long as they\rquote re good rugby players, I wouldn\rquote 
t mind\'94.  \'93Fine\'94, he said, \'93That\rquote s all\'94!  (LAUGHS)  And then that evening, a list was put up, \'93The follow cadets are assigned to the Indian Army\'94
.  (LAUGHS)  It really was as simple as that!  So instead of going to the normal officer training in Britain, I was shipped out to \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. (INAUDIBLE \endash 
 330) in Central India, and did my officer training there.  And I liked the Indian Army.  I mean, it was \'85 it was War time, bits of it were very unpleasant.  And another of those small coincidences 
is that the young man in the room next to me was Colin Rosser, who, of course, became Rosser and Harris, of the study in Swansea.  I didn\rquote t know that, and I \'85
 when I went to Swansea to be interviewed for the Chair, I met Colin, who was a Research Fellow there, and he said, \'93Are you the \'85\'94  He said, \'93You\rquote re not Gosforth Williams, are you?\'94  (LAUGHS)  And that\rquote 
s how we connected that!  So I spent four years in the Indian Army and then came back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Mmm.  And you were saying that that had an impact in terms of seeing a different society.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Oh, absolutely!  I mean, the first thing was that I had an \'93orderly\'94 - you call them \'93batman\'94 in the English Army, in the British Army - an orderly, who brushed my boots and brought me tea in the morning.  It was
 a servant, and I found this extraordinary, you know, that there\rquote s a man here who\rquote s actually a servant!  I\rquote d read about it in books about Victorian England and so on!  And it was a very hierarchical \'85
 the Indian Army is very hierarchical, with the vast maj
ority of officers being British, and a small number being Indian, very small number.  And I was one of them, I was one of the European British officers, almost all of whom were public school boys, and made fun of my Welsh accent \endash 
 but in a kindly sort of way.  And the other thing about it, of course, was that a lot of it was, I think accidental, that the time I was in was in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid9530551 Jat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  (?? \endash  354) Regiment, which was a \'85 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid9530551 Jat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
 were Hindu peasants from Central India, but they had two Companies of people who were called \'93Muslims\'94, or \'93Musselmans\'94
, so there were two Musselman Companies, and two Hindu Companies, and they lived entirely separate.  I mean, they fought together, but they had different diets, and their religions were different.  I mean, they could ju
st as easily have been in different worlds, in a sense.  I mean, you got to learn this very quickly.  I mean, you knew that there were some things you could say to Hindus, you could not say to this one \'85 the way you greeted them, you said, \'93Ram, ram
\'94 to Hindus and so forth.  And you had to learn the language, of course.  I went to Munchi (?? \endash  365) to learn the language, so that I could speak \'85 in my case, because I was in a Hindu Company, I learnt to speak Hindi, whereas if I\rquote 
d been in a Musselman Company, I\rquote d have learnt to speak Urdu, and to write Urdu.  And because I was fairly good at it, I was actually encouraged to go on and do the Interpreter\rquote 
s Exam, which I did, and I was paid an extra two rupees, or something like that, a week!  (LAUGHS)  So, high powered!  (LAUGHS)  But that made me very conscious that India wasn\rquote 
t India, it was a collection of different groups and so forth.  And then, of course, I was still in the Army when India broke up into India and Pakistan, and I was told that I\rquote d have to le
ave the Indian Army and be repatriated, and I ended up in the South Wales Borderers, appropriately enough in Brecon!  So I\rquote d come full circle as it were.  But that, together with Alwyn\rquote 
s influence, I think, later made me realise that the world wasn\rquote t as homogeneous a place as I thought it was.  But I\rquote ve never been back to India, I\rquote 
ve never been back since those days.  I sometimes wonder whether it would be a sensible thing \'85  The other thing that happened, I suppose it\rquote s relevant, was that towards the end o
f my career in the Far East - I was in Java during the unpleasantness in Java, and it was extremely unpleasant - I was sent to Sumatra, to M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid9530551 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 dan (?? \endash  391), where there was a small sort of Headquarters, and this was to prepare for the Dutch coming back to take control of Java and Sumatra, but they didn\rquote t, because they were defeated by 
\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. (INAUDIBLE \endash  395).  But not long after I arrived, I was told I had to go up to a place about 40 miles outside M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid9530551 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 dan, to be stationed in the Japanese \'85 Imperial 
Japanese Guards Division, to prepare for them to go back to Japan.  So off I went in a Jeep, and I arrived there, and these Japanese soldiers were all fully armed, because there had been no one to disarm them, so there I was, with 12,000 fully armed Japan
ese, on my own, right \'85 (LAUGHS), waiting to convey instructions to them.  And the colonel in charge of this \endash  the other thing is, they were all over six foot, right, so although one thinks of the Japanese as being short, I was the smallest \'85
 smallest man in the place!  (LAUGHS)  The colonel had been educated in Oxford, so he spoke immaculate English.  And I was put in a hut.  And then I became \'85
 and then encountered a very very different sort of culture.  Very different.  I mean, not only highly disciplined, but so different \'85 in a way that India wasn\rquote 
t different.  I mean, India had been under British rule for a long time, so certain things you could take for granted, I mean, their legal system was the British legal system with British judges and so forth, w
hereas the Japanese were not European in any sense at all, and \'85 um \'85 I realised that I was a complete outsider \endash  in every sense, a complete outsider.  And I was there about five or six months \'85
 five months, perhaps, before, eventually, I went down with them to M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid9530551 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
dan, and they were put on an aircraft carrier and sent back to Japan.  So that made me realise that, you know, there was another entirely different \'85 well, I had great difficulty in \'85 um \'85
 understanding how to behave in this very enclosed society.  I mean, for example, I once said to the colonel that I\rquote d like a haircut.  He said, \'93Okay, you can have a haircut\'94
.  And two days later, a barber turned up, who was from New Jersey originally, with a very strong American accent, and he cut my hair, and I chatted to him, and I said, you know, \'93What do you \'85 how do you feel about being stationed here?\'94
  And he said, \'93Oh no, no, no, I\rquote m not stationed here, I come from Pa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid9530551 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 ang (?? \endash  435) \endash 
 now, Pa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid9530551 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 ang was the other side of Sumatra, about 400 miles away \endash  and 
the Japanese had decided that I should have my hair cut, not by a Japanese barber, but by someone who was familiar with European or American haircuts, so they brought this man up about 400 miles!  (LAUGHS) \'85
 in a Jeep, to cut my hair, and then go back again!  And I thought, \'93There\rquote s a world here that is different from my world\'94.  So I then started reading \'85 you know, what little there was \endash  Ruth Benedict, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Samson and the Sword}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  (?? \endash  444) and so forth, I thought I \'85 \'93This is just purely \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85
\'85\'85..\'94 (INAUDIBLE \endash  445), but, nevertheless, I mean, I think it was useful in my general education.
