\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2758831 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Well, if I had, it would have been in India, I think, because Japanese \'85 I rapidly realised that Japanese was an extremely difficult language, and Chinese even more difficult!  I ended up in Singapore, in the \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85.. (INAUDIBLE 
\endash  451) Headquarters in Singapore, as a Staff Officer, and the staff were all Chinese, and, I mean, listening to Chinese talking Mandarin or Cantonese, made me realise that this \'85 I just didn\rquote 
t think I was good enough to do it.  I could have done it in India, I suppose, but \'85 I don\rquote t think it ever occurred to me.  I think, having come back to this countr
y, and gone back to Aberystwyth, the thought of going back to India, or to Singapore for that matter, simply seemed, to me, to be too big a step, although I had actually \'85 um \'85 one of these sort of coincidences that influences one\rquote s life \'85
 as I was finishing the research on Gosforth, I thought, \'93I\rquote ve got to get myself a job\'94, so I applied for a job with the Colonial Service, and went through a series of interviews, and I had all the right credentials \endash  I\rquote 
d been an Officer in the Indian Army, was a graduate 
and so forth.  I was interviewed by a whole series of people, and the last person who interviewed me was a retired District Commissioner, I think, from East Africa, and he interviewed me, and at the end he said, \'93I\rquote 
m going to recommend that we give you a post, but I think you\rquote d be much better off becoming an academic\'94.  (LAUGHS)  Extraordinary!  So I said, \'93Thanks very much\'94
.  And the final interview, in the Colonial Office, which was a formality, was on the same day as the interview in Keele, for the job.  I knew it was a formality, so I rang the Colonial Office and said, \'93
Look, I have to be honest with you.  I have an opportunity for another kind of job, and I understand the interview is a formality, and it happens every two weeks, or four weeks, or whatever, can I defer it?\'94  And they said, \'93
No.  You either come to the interview or you lose the job\'94.  So I had to decide between the bird in the hand, or the speculative bird in the bush!  And I went to Keele, and what I hadn\rquote t realised, at the time, was that
 I was one of something like 85 applicants for the job at Keele, for Assistant Lecturer!  (LAUGHS)  But I got it.  And I\rquote ve sometimes wondered since \endash  not recently \endash  what would have happened if I\rquote 
d gone and become an Assistant District Commissioner in Kenya, which would have been a short life, of course, because not long after that, the East African countries became Independent, and the Colonial Office packed up, so I\rquote 
d be moved into the Civil Service or something like that.  So that was one of those \'85 but I thought it was very interesting that this man, on the basis of half an hour\rquote s conversation, decided that I was of an academic cast of mind, because \'85
 I mean, he asked me about life in India, and \'85 so it was the way we were talking, I suppose.  So when Alwyn said, \'93Why don\rquote t you go and study an English village?\'94 I thought I\rquote d go and study an English village.
