\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid1732375 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Well, I was married by this time, and my wife was a Cumbrian, and taught in Gosforth, so I thought I might consider going to do Gosforth.  Now, Gosforth had two 
attractions.  The first was, and this, of course, is typical of the community studies at the time, that you wanted somewhere that was really isolated, something that was not contaminated by urban life.  I wanted the true picture of rural life, so there I 
w
as, doing Gosforth, and there were people doing the same in remote Welsh villages, and Jimmy Littlejohn was doing the same in Scotland, because community studies were about remote communities, and the general sort of idea, at the time, was that this was f
i
ne.  However, Gosforth had an additional attraction to me, and that was, it was three miles from Seascale, which later became known as Sellafield.  So while I was walking round the farms and the village in Gosforth, I could see the towers of the Atomic En
ergy Authority growing up, and a lot of the farm labourers from Gosforth, had gone to work in Sellafield, because it was better paid.  But it was only just starting, so that it couldn\rquote 
t be, as I saw it at the time, a study of the most modern advanced technology on rural life.  I mean, it was relatively isolated, and the people who \'85 they built \'85
 Seascale was a small village, and they built a lot of houses for the staff who worked in the Atomic Energy, so these were imported, these were imported physicists an
d engineers, and had nothing in common with the people that lived in the thing around them.  Nevertheless, I thought this was an additional bonus.  So I went \'85
