\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid1732375 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Hadn\rquote 
t changed very much.  And I went to see the Headmaster at the village school, a man called Will Wilson, who said, \'93Now, you should really start without \'85\'94 \'85
 the plan was to do the farms around the village first, and then with the village last.  \'93You should with the old standards\'94.  He said, \'93Yes, these are the well-established farmers, the \'85\'94 what we call \'93yeoman farmers\'94, \'93
so go and see Matt Sherwin.  I\rquote ll ring him up and tell him you\rquote re coming\'94.  So I went to see Matthew Sherwin \'85 who was very hospitable, and whose family had been on that farm since 1603, or something like this.  And then he said, \'93
You go and see my brother\'94.  So I went to see his brother, and his brother was on that \'85
 had been on the farm since 17-something or other.  And then I followed this trail from one old standards farm to another, and I was immensely impressed by the fact that a small family could actually sort of hold on to this piec
e of land over the centuries, and it reminded me of the name of the land in Arensberg, and I thought, \'93This is the name on the land, and this is what drives the family system, its continuity\'94.  And then when I\rquote 
d finished this, I went to farmers who were not old standards.  There was a man called Boulton who\rquote d just bought a mechanical potato digger, and was regarded as weird!  He was known as \'93Agnew and his tater digger\'94
 because no one had had a mechanical \'85!  (LAUGHS)  So, having done that, and at the same time I was looking at the Parish Records, and I could see the Sherwins going back to the 17}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f42\fs22\super\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  century, and others going back, and I thought, \'93This is \'85 this is a perfect example of stability and history\'94
, and in a sense it was \endash  at least, I thought it was.
  And then I did the village, and similarly, in the village, I think the vast majority of the villagers had been born in Gosforth, and their parents had been born in Gosforth, so if you looked at the Parish Registers you saw names that recurred and recurr
e
d, so I thought that was the kind of society it was, and I came to the view that, in fact, this was so resistant to the Sellafields of this world, that it would survive relatively unchanged, in spite of this funny thing going up on the horizon.  And the s
t
udy was seen in terms of a very self-sufficient, enclosed community, but also, of course, very highly stratified, because living in the village, there were people who were of a different class.  And I remember, one of these was a man called Jefferson, who
 was the wine merchant in Whitehaven \endash  public schoolboy, his daughters had both been to public schools as well \endash 
 and I went to interview him, very courteous, and he told me about his family and so forth, and he was, self-evidently, a public school boy.  But
 then when I went to events in the village, I noticed that when he talked to the villagers, he talked in a Cumbrian accent, and when he saw people of his own class, he talked with a \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. (INAUDIBLE \endash 
 033) pronunciation.  And I thought, \'93This man sort of sees himself as being able to move from one world to another, fairly effortlessly\'94
.  And I also discovered, of course, that the majority of the villagers thought he was being patronising (LAUGHS) in trying to talk like them, as it were, whereas some of the others made no attempt to speak in the local dialect \'85
 I mean, there was a retired colonel there, and he behaved like a retired colonel \endash  all the time.  But these were \'85 although Jefferson was slightly unusual, the other people who were there \endash  like the retired colonel \endash 
 were outsiders who\rquote d come to live in the village, no roots in the village, and they would always be outsiders, nothing they could do to make themselves insiders.  So I saw this as a very cohesive, very powerful community, and kinship 
very important, because one would learn, very quickly \'85 I mean, I learnt, very quickly, you should never criticise anyone, and traps would be laid for you.  They would say \'85
 there was a family called the Mossops, who were regarded as rather wild, and, of course, reputation went on family lines.  If you were a Mossop, it didn\rquote 
t matter.  However respective of the law, straight-laced you were, you were a Mossop, and, therefore, you were expected to be wild.  If you were a Sherwin, you were expected to be stabl
e and so forth.  And I went to see (LAUGHS), I went to see Will Mossop, and they \'85
 were very courteous, they were very friendly and so on.  The thing that made it slightly unusual was that when I went into the farmyard, there was a sort of elderly lady wan
dering around the farmyard, and when I went to knock at the door, half a brick sort of whizzed past my head!  (LAUGHS)  Mrs. Mossop opened the door and said, \'93Stop it!  Auntie!\'94  (LAUGHS)  It was this \'85 she said, \'93Don\rquote 
t worry about my aunt, she\rquote s a bit odd!\'94  (LAUGHS)  Anyway, the Mossops.  So a couple of days later, I went somewhere else, and someone said, \'93I hear you\rquote ve been to see Will Mossop and his family\'94, so I said, \'93Yes, I have\'94.  
\'93They\rquote re a funny lot\'94, they said.  \'93Oh\'94, I said, \'93They were extremely friendly and so forth\'94.  \'93Oh, we thought you\rquote d find them a bit funny\'94, and I said, \'93No, no, I didn\rquote t\'94
.  And then, of course, I discovered that the person who I was talking to was a Graham, his wife had been a Mossop, and they were trying to see if I would say \'85 because if I had, they\rquote d have told the Mossops, \'93This person\rquote 
s making fun of you\'94.  So the network was there.  And from collecting the genealogies, I was able to establish the network, not that it meant that there was invariably co-operation, becaus
e there were some feuds in the sort of families, which prevented wholesale co-operation, and this was where Max Gluckman had been an influence on me, because I\rquote d read Max\rquote s piece in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The Feud}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , which showed how you \'85 conflict was managed, and this influenced what I, you know, kinderreitel\'85\'85
., people who never spoke to me, although had relatives or kindred that were not recognised.  This was when I first found the notion of recognition.  And I went to a farm, the Pooles, and there were two children playing rou
nd my feet, so I did the family history, as I called it, and wrote it all down, put it all down, and there was no mention of these children at all.  Well, I was sensible enough not to ask about these children.  So I said, \'93Is that everyone?\'94  \'93
Oh yes\'94.  \'93And there\rquote s Auntie so and so in Australia\'94, but nothing about the children, or the children\rquote s \'85 apparently the children\rquote 
s mother.  And I discovered, afterwards, that these two children were the illegitimate daughters of the unmarried daughter, who lived wit
h them.  Other people, like, identified these.  Now, they were invisible to the outside world.  They were simply invisible to the outside world.  And since I was the outside world, I had no business enquiring who they were.  And there were lots of things 
like this, that the village recognised as being \'85 sort of seen as inappropriate by the outside world, but they accepted that this was what life was like.  So it was a very cohesive system.  But, of course, it was changing.  And I went to \'85
 I went back to Gosforth last year, for the first time since I left, and it has been transformed, because it\rquote s now a tourist village, it\rquote 
s got piles of gift shops and cafes and things like this, and when I did my study, there were no gift shops and no cafes.  There wasn\rquote t a caf\'e9
 at all, and now there must be half a dozen cafes and lots of gift shops and things like this, so tourism has transformed the village of Connery (?? \endash  082).  How far it\rquote s transformed the farms, I don\rquote 
t know, because I have no means of finding out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid5898397 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
So you actually lived in the village when you were doing the study?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 No, I \'85
 well, I spent all my time in the village, actually spent part of the time living in the village, but otherwise I lived with my wife\rquote s parents, just outside the village, because it was a convenient thing to do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Mmm.  And you were describing the kind of method which was partly observing, but also interviewing people.  Is that right?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Well, I\rquote 
d three methods.  First of all, I had \'85 this was Alwyn.  Alwyn said, \'93You have to collect statistics\'94.  He said, \'93You have to collect statistics\'94
, so I had to collect statistics!  So I drew up a questionnaire with his help, which asked basic questions of every family that I interviewed, sort of genealogical questions
, but also age, occupation, owner-occupiers/tenants, things like that, so I had this basic data that I collected for every household in the village, and only in one case did I actually have to have it done at second hand \endash  this was a family called 
\'93The Hermits\'94, who lived up on a remote farm \endash  and I met the postman, I was going up, and he said, \'93Don\rquote t waste your time, because I\rquote ve been delivering the post there for 20 years, and I\rquote ve never seen them!\'94
  So I had \'85 that was the sort of basic data, which allowed me to say things about the demography of the village, I suppose, and quite a lot about the economy, the farm economy \endash  I\rquote 
d ask how many cows they had, how many sheep, how much land and so on \endash  I drew maps of the farm holdings.  And then I did interviews, so I interviewed someone in every household, except The Hermits.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
And you took notes of those?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
I took notes, yes.  And what I did, actually, was \endash  this was before the days of tape-recorders, and if you\rquote d had a tape-recorder, it would hav
e been the size of a small suitcase!  There was a bridge over a stream, just outside the village, and I used to take my lunch with me, sandwiches.  When I\rquote d finished in the morning, I would rush and go underneath the bridge, where I couldn\rquote 
t be seen, and I\rquote d eat my lunch, and I\rquote d write up as much of the verbatim comments that I could remember, against the sort of skeleton that I had of the notes as I went along.  So if someone said something that was particularly striking, I
\rquote d tried to memorise it and write it down.  I got very good at this, actually, with practice.  So that\rquote s \'85 that was recorded.  And then I \'85 it was participant observation \endash 
 well, participant and non-participant!  Anything that was on, I went to.  \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. Academy who didn\rquote t come \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85 (INAUDIBLE \endash 
 112) wrestling they had once a month, where I\rquote d go and sit and watch them, and talk to people.  And there was the Dramatic Society.  And I went to the Gospel Show, and things like that, and wrote these down and tried to identify \'85
\par 
\par [BREAK IN RECORDING]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Yes, you were talking about participant observation.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
And I would try to record everyone who attended anything, and who the office holders were, so I discovered that a small group of people were actually the office holders
 in most voluntary Organisations, you know, the Secretary of one thing would be the Secretary or Chairman of another.  They drove the social life of the village.  I would then try to match up the sort of material with the interviews, and I also discovered
 the good informant \endash  these were the days when anthropologists made much of the good informant \endash  and I found half a dozen people who were willing to talk, endlessly, about life in the village, and didn\rquote t mind \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Who were they, then?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Well, there was the local shoemaker, who \'85 er \'85 Bill Smail (?? Snail?? \endash  127), who saw people \'85 was well connected, in kinship terms, but knew everybody in the village, and worked out what I was \'85
 I told everyone I was writing a history of the village.  The story was, if I\rquote d said I was doing a thesis, it wouldn\rquote t make much sense to them, so I said, \'93I\rquote 
m writing a history of the village, but right up to the present day because I want to show how the village, today, relates to its history\'94, which was true, up to a point!  And Bill Smail sort of questioned me very tactfully about this, and said \'85
 um \'85 \'93What you\rquote re trying to do is to \'85 you know, work out how we live\'94, as it were.  He\rquote d apprehended, I think, what the nature of the exercise was.  So he would produ
ce analyses of various things that were going on in the village, that he thought would be of interest to me.  The schoolmaster, Will Wilson, was useful.  There was a \'85 the Parish Clerk, who was the coalman when he wasn\rquote 
t being Parish Clerk, and some of the farmers \endash 
 the Sherwins were extremely hospitable and would tell me a lot about farmers and farming and so forth.  I mean, they all had their own perspectives.  But I could call in to see them at any time, and they\rquote d give me a cup of tea, and they\rquote 
d say, in so many words, \'93What do you want to talk about now?\'94  So I would say, \'93Well, I\rquote ve been looking at sheep farming, and it doesn\rquote t quite make sense, you know, can you \'85\'94
 and they would tell me about sheep farming, and things like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 So you were 
trying out some of your ideas on them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Yes I was.  Yes, I was.  I\rquote d \'85 um \'85 in fact, some of the ideas, I think I\rquote d taken, as it were, ready-made, and weren\rquote t entirely \'85 sensible?  I don\rquote t know if that\rquote s the word.  I\rquote d read }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The Yankee City}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  series, Lloyd Warner, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The Yankee City}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
 series, and thought this was great, and I was much taken with their ideas about social stratification.  So I thought, \'93This will \'85 this will work in Gosforth.  It\rquote ll give me a framework to look at stratification in Gosforth\'94. 
 So a lot of the questions were directed at seeing how far I could use this framework.  And one of the things I did, which I was fairly pleased with, was, I asked a lot of people what they thought of \'85 let\rquote s call them \'93other classes\'94 or 
\'93other status groups\'94
, so that if you sort of arrayed the status groups, you could say that if you were middle-middle, as it were, your perspectives on these groups would be different from someone higher up or lower down.  And the higher up you went, the less knowledge and r
ecognition there was of the people down at the bottom.  And similarly, if you started at the bottom \endash  and there was a bottom \endash 
 their knowledge of the different strata, sort of faded as they went upwards, you know, they were snobs or toffs, or whatever, you didn\rquote t have anything to do with them, you never had anything \'85
 so that gave me a sort of picture.  But, of course, on reflection afterwards, I mean, this was a framework that was imposed, although it was quite useful, so that was one thing.  But otherwise
, I think that a lot of the ideas, as I say, are people like Arensberg and Alwyn.  I tried to see how far an English village would resemble a remote Welsh, Welsh-speaking village, and in what ways it differed.  It obviously differed in being Anglican, and
 \'85 um \'85 but \'85 I don\rquote t think I actually saw it as a deeply analytical and theoretically based piece.  I think, like \'85
 I think, many of us who did community studies in those days, saw ourselves as really giving a sort of a narrative, an account of what life was \'85 what it felt like to live in a place like Gosforth.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Sort of like a documentary, in a way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Almost.  Almost.  And I think this is partly how it was seen.  I mean, I think that \'85 I assumed, for example, that history was very important.  I assumed that if I looked at the Parish Records and worked out what had happened in the tithe \'85\'85\'85
\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. (INAUDIBLE \endash  178) and looked at enclosures and things like this, this would help to inform my understanding of the way farming was.  Well, yes, it di
d, up to a point.  But, I mean, I did far more history, and collected far more historical data than I really needed to, in terms of using it in explaining how the village was, because, for example, there was one group of five houses in one end of the vill
age, which had vanished.  I became quite interested, for a time, in the notion of folk memory, how accurate folk memory was, so I\rquote 
d ask people about these five houses, and no one had heard of them, and most people refused to believe they existed, because they\rquote 
d completely vanished, and the field was just a field.  And this made me curious about these five houses, and who lived in them, it was curiosity.  So I tried to find out a lot about them, but it was absolutely \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85
 (INAUDIBLE \endash  190) what was going on in Gosforth at the time.  But I enjoyed it, I mean, I enjoyed analysing the Parish Records for its own sake really.  And I did the same in Ashworthy as well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
And in terms of the participant observation, were you active \'85 like did you play cricket, or go to the church?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid32457 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
No.  In fact, the one occasion when I was asked to participate, was when I was invited to take part in a wrestling match!  And I realised that I would be thoroughly punished if I did, so I refused!  And the other things, I mean, Dramatic Society was \'85
 the Dramatic Society.  I went to the church, I attended the church services, but they \'85 realised, very rapidly, that I wasn\rquote t an Anglican, and \'85 I mean, to look forward, this presented me with a dilemma when I went to North L
ew to do the Ashworthy Study, because that had an Anglican Church and a Methodist Chapel, and these were two different sets.  So my first dilemma was, \'93Should I go to both, or neither, or one?\'94
  So I actually went to both.  And this completely baffled everyone.  \'93How could you go to an Anglican Service }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\ul\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  go to the Methodist Chapel?\'94  And people \'85 it took me a long time to allay the suspicion, of doing this absolutely extraordinary thing.  It didn\rquote 
t arise in Gosforth because there was, essentially, just the Anglican Church, which wasn\rquote t terribly well attended.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2099945 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
So what was the participant observation, what Organisation, do you think, was the most interesting?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2099945 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
I think it was probably the Agricultural Show.  Not simply the Show itself, but all the work that led up to it, because it was a big event in the year and, incidentally, one of the reasons why the Mossops were regarded as rather \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85
\'85\'85\'85\'85 (INAUDIBLE \endash  214) was that they had a jumping competition for young women, who would come along, and they probably used to jump, and Matt Mossop\rquote 
s son came with his ponies and went round the course and knocked down every single test, quite deliberately (LAUGHS) like a trail of destruction (LAUG
HS) before sort of going off!  But they had endless sub-committees, you know, one to do the Riding Competitions, one to do the livestock, and things like this was interrelated, and systems were reporting up, and there were all sorts of disagreements about
 what was the most appropriate thing.  So I found that I wasn\rquote t entirely welcome, actually, with these.  I think they thought, \'93What\rquote s this outsider doing coming to our Committee Meeting?\'94
  But I was there on sufferance.  The thing they wouldn\rquote t let me do w
as take notes.  What do I do down there?  So I had to try and remember as much of it as I possibly could!  (LAUGHS)  Which I did.  And as soon as I went, came out, I would write it down, frantically, to remember who was there and what they said, and what 
the issues were.  So I found that useful.  The school had a sort of active \'85 PTA, I suppose it would be called now, so I would go there, and the Headmaster was sort of \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. (INAUDIBLE \endash 
 230) he allowed me to do that.  Was there anything else?  I\rquote m trying to think.  But there were no political Organisations.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid2099945 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 And you \'85\'85\'85
