\i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The Country Craftsman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  had been about country crafts in Devon, and in Llanforest \endash 
 a comparative study.  So I went down to Devon, again I was seized with this notion of remoteness, and I went around and stayed in six villages, like Torrington, North Lew and so forth, to see if I could find out which of them I would choose.  I\rquote 
m afraid the final choice was almost completely unscientific!  The reason I chose North Lew was, first of all, it had a good \'85 I suppose an entirely unscientific \'85 a good collection of Parish Records, which I wanted.  If you\rquote 
re going to study depopulation, you need good Parish Records.  And the other thing was that it had a nice pub called \'93The Green Dragon\'94, and very friendly people.  And all the other places I went to, like Torrington and 
things like this, I thought the people were extremely unfriendly, and I thought, \'93If I\rquote m going to do this study, I might as well do it in a friendly place\'94
, so I chose North Lew, and then went down from Keele and lived in it for two long vacations, and did the study.  And it was at this time that I thought, \'93Well, now, if it\rquote 
s depopulation, is this likely to have an effect on farming, and so forth?\'94  And before I did it, I decided I would revisit the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Gosforth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  material, because it seemed to me that, in fact, there weren\rquote t farmers of the old standards in North Lew \endash  and we\rquote ll call it \'93Ashworthy\'94 \endash 
 in the sense that the same families had occupied the same farms for generation after generation.  Something different was happening.  Well, of course, what happened was, when I actually analysed }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Gosforth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
 material, I discovered that the old standards were actually a minority of the farmers in Gosforth, a very prominent and striking minority, but, nevertheless, most of the farmers in Gosforth, are like Boulton and his tatie digger, who\rquote 
d been on the farm about five or six years.  And more than half of them \endash  I can\rquote t remember, say two-thirds of them \endash 
 had actually moved into their farms in the previous ten years, so the continuity that I saw as the hallmark of Gosforth, was illusory.  So it made me think, \'93
Well, what have I missed here?  And what mechanisms had been in place to account for this thing?\'94  So I \'85 I \'85 again, as in Gosforth, I started with the farms.  And I went around, and I found only one farm, a man called Greythread (?? \endash 
 061), I think, whose family had been on the farm for three generations, all the others were more recent.  But equally interesting was that although they were more recent, a substantial proportion of them were local.  There were some incomers, \'93
Up Country Johnnies\'94 they were called, the people who\rquote d left other occupations to become farmers, because land was cheap in Devon, they didn\rquote t realise it was cheap for a reason, and \'85 but most of them \'85
 I remember the particular incident that gave rise to this idea - because one needs an idea \endash  I was in the pub, as \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. (INAUDIBLE \endash  069), and I\rquote 
d come back and have an evening meal in the pub, and after the evening meal, I\rquote d play darts \endash  to get to know the local people.  And this chap came in, this farmer came in, and I started talking to him, and he said, \'93Oh yes, I\rquote 
ve heard you\rquote ve been going around\'94.  He said, \'93Well, I\rquote m moving tomorrow\'94.  So I said, \'93Yes\'94.  He said, \'93I\rquote m moving from Such and Such a farm, to Such and Such a farm\'94.  So I said, \'93Well, what\rquote 
s the difference?\'94  He said, \'93The \'85 not much difference really, they\rquote ve both got 90 acres.  I think the farm I\rquote m moving to is a better farm\'94, you know, \'93but it\rquote s not all that much of a change\'94.  So I thought, \'93
Well, why is this man moving?\'94  Moving, particularly if you\rquote re a farmer, is a difficult thing to do.  So I thought, \'93
Right, I will incorporate into the study of depopulation, a notion of farmers as a mobile entity, and see how that relates to depopulation\'94.  And, of course, the paradox was th
at, at the end of the study, I could not explain (LAUGHS) this particular farmer moving from one farm to another, because it was completely quixotic!  I mean, he\rquote 
d just done it, whereas most had good reasons for doing it.  So then I started off looking at the farmers, and found that you could relate the mobility to family structure and things like this, and it was a much more fluid \'85
