ght?  To get a good idea.  And I was looking at Arensberg, because Arensberg was, as you will have gathered, an important influence in my life, and I thought, \'93Well, I like Ireland, where the name is on the land.  These farmers don\rquote 
t have their name on the land.  There is no pressure to try and keep a particular farm in the same family.  They\rquote re prepared to move around\'94.  So what are the sort of mechanisms that allow farmers to, or requiring farmers to move, if there
\rquote s no name on the land?  And out of this came this idea of \'85 that the family ideology required \endash  required is too strong a word \endash  a farmer to find farms for all his sons, because if you\rquote 
ve got two sons, only one son can stay in the farm, another son\rquote s got to move somewhere else, or possibly they\rquote ll all move and then find two different farms.  So what I did was, I tried to work out \endash  and I think I did work out 
\endash  how the dynamics of the family, and the absence of the name on the land, allowed farmers to move from one farm to another.  And you\rquote d get i
t working through generations that some, like the Adams family, for example, had moved, over two generations, to different farms.  It \'85 it didn\rquote t always work, of course, because some farmers didn\rquote t have sons, and farmers didn\rquote 
t like daughters becoming farmers \endash  any more than they did in Ireland, where you have the son-in-laws sort of marrying in \endash  and some of them, the sons didn\rquote t want to become farmers.  They left, because they didn\rquote t want to go 
\'85  I mean, I produced a model, I suppose it was, that I thought fitted this, and this was a much more dynamic model than \'85 compared to Gosforth.  The one thing I didn\rquote 
t do, and I should have done, I suppose, I might have done, was actually apply that to the Gosforth material to see if it worked against methods of \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. (INAUDIBLE \endash 
 113), but I was so ashamed of having missed the significance of \'85 I didn\rquote t have the courage to go and read the Gosforth material in the light of that!  So that\rquote s how North Lew \'85
 and then I did the village, actual village itself, which h
ad been much affected by depopulation.  That was much more a classical account of young people leaving to get work in places round about, or Exeter, or Okehampton, or wherever it was.  That was rather more straightforward and, in a sense, less interesting
,
 because it was the farmers that really interested me.  So that was a sort of change.  And the thing about getting an idea, I owe that to Cicourel, actually.  Again, one of these happy coincidences one has in academic life.  Cicourel was a Visiting Profes
sor in Bristol, I think, and the University of Wales has a Conference Centre called \'93Gregannog\'94 (?? Sp) in mid-Wales \endash 
 beautiful building, which two sisters had given to the University of Wales - and you could use as a Conference Centre.  And each university \endash  each of the Colleges \endash  could have it for a set period, and it was back in \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85
\'85\'85 (INAUDIBLE \endash  127) it was my turn to go to Gregannog, so we had a weekend on methodology, actually.  Methodology.  And we heard that Cicourel was in the country, so I wro
te and asked him if he would come and talk to us, and he wrote back a charming letter saying, \'93Well, that\rquote s what I\rquote m in this country for.  Yes, I will come and talk\'94
.  So Cicourel came and read what I thought was one of the best papers I\rquote ve ever heard in m
y life.  It was absolutely stunning!  And it went down like a lead balloon, because the majority were post-graduate students, and some of my colleagues, and I don\rquote t think they\rquote 
d really understood what he was talking about!  And what Cicourel said was, he t
alked about his work on the deaf and things like this, and what he said in the middle of this talk - which had some absolutely incredible stories in, I might say, wonderful anecdotes \endash  he said, \'93
American post-graduate students are trained in methodology an
d methods, so that they worked their way through Goode and Hatt, and Lazarsfeld and things like this, and they knew exactly what to do with data, and how to analyse it and set it out, and things like this.\'94  He said, \'93
The thing that none of these books tell you is how to get a good idea\'94.  And he said, \'93I can\rquote t tell you how you get a good idea.  The only thing you can do is to sit down and think about your data, and hope that you get a good idea\'94
.  Right?  Well, I thought that was wonderful.  The students thought it was terrible because it didn\rquote t tell them how to get a good idea!  So when I was sitting looking at the Ashworthy data, I thought, \'93What I need is a good idea!\'94
  (LAUGHS)  Because I\rquote d got everything laid out, I can see, you know, how it\rquote s working,
 but I need a good idea.  And I think I sat, I seem to recall I sat for three to four weeks, and eventually I got the good idea that this was to do with the relationship between family succession and land-holding, and once I got that good idea, it all fel
l into place.  But \'85 so \'85 Cicourel should be grateful for that!  I didn\rquote t write to tell him, actually, but I thought he was an absolutely wonderful man.  And as a result of that, I read a lot of his work, because I have read }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Method and Measurement}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , and things like that before, I knew he was there.  And he told a story that
\rquote s worth repeating, I think, if I may?
