\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid8588501 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
He bet him a hundred dollars he would do this.  Right?  So he went into the Governor\rquote s office, offices, and he said to his friend, \'93Now, you do exactly what I tell you\'94.  So he said, \'93
Tell your secretary you do not want to be interrupted, under any circumstances\'94.  So the chap said, \'93Beverley, we do not want to be interrupted\'94.  And they went in, and Circourel opened his briefcase, and
 took out crosswords and gave them to his friend.  Sat there doing the crossword.  Complete silence.  And he\rquote d also said to the secretary, \'93No calls.  Don\rquote t want any calls\'94
.  So they do this for a while, and the secretary knocks at the door, they hide the crosswords, the secretary comes in and says, \'93Would you like coffee?\'94  He said, \'93Yes, we\rquote d like \'85\'94  \'93Everything all right?\'94  \'93
Yes, everything\rquote s fine.  Everything\rquote s absolutely fine\'94.  So the secretary brings in the coffee.  \'93Are you sure \'85?\'94  \'93Everything\rquote s fine.  No more calls\'94
.  So they sit there.  And then at lunch time, he puts his head round the door and says, \'93We\rquote re now going to lunch, Beverley\'94.  But we\rquote re not having lunch.  Shut the door.  Complete silence.  And this was one of these offices where the
y had partitions that didn\rquote t go right to the ceiling, so there\rquote s complete silence.  And shortly after lunch, the Governor rings, right?  And says, \'93I hear something\rquote s up, Pat\'94.  And Pat said, \'93
No, no, nothing at all, Governor.  Everything\rquote s fine.  Everything\rquote s absolutely fine\'94.  \'93Are you sure about that?\'94  \'93Yes, I\rquote m absolutely sure\'94, Pat says.  \'93Oh fine\'94
, said the Governor, rings off.  And they go on doing the crossword, no telephone conversations, no phone calls.  Come about three o\rquote clock, there\rquote s a knock at the door, and Beverley said, \'93The Governor\rquote s on his way to see you\'94
.  And they put the crosswords away, and the Governor comes in.  He knows Cicourel, so he acknowledges Cicourel.  \'93Is everything fine?\'94  \'93Yes\'94, Pat says, \'93Everything\rquote s absolutely fine.  
No, nothing unusual whatsoever, Governor.  Absolutely fine\'94.  And the Governor said, \'93Now, come on.  Come clean.  Now, what\rquote s going on\'94.  Right?  \'93Why aren\rquote t you taking calls?\'94  And Pat said, \'93Well, it\rquote 
s nothing, Governor, we just wanted to be \'85 we just wanted to be on our own so we could do some work\'94.  And the Governor said, \'93No, no, no.  Can\rquote t be right.  What are you up to?\'94  And he said, \'93
People are talking about you all over the building!\'94  And the more Pat said, \'93Everything\rquote s fine\'94, the more suspicious the Governor became, and left.  And Cicourel said, \'93
You owe me a hundred dollars, because this chap no longer trusts you.  The more you assure him that nothing is wrong, the more suspicious he becomes, because you\rquote re behaving in a \'85 an unusual way.  And although you\rquote 
ve been working for this chap all these years, you know, he doesn\rquote t trust you\'94.  So he handed over the $100 and left.  And then the postscript of this was that Cicourel said, \'93Look, go and see the Governor tomorrow morning, and tell him that 
it was a kind of social science experiment to see how \endash  don\rquote t say it was to do with trust \endash  how to \'85 to test how the Organisation works\'94.  So Pat went along and saw the Governor, and the Governor didn\rquote 
t believe him!  And it took him about a week before, eventually, the Governor thought that it had been a silly experiment.  And Cicourel said, \'93What is the moral of this story?\'94
  And everybody looked absolutely blank, all the students looked blank, and Cicourel said, \'93Trust is not cumulative\'94 (?? 197).  I thoug
ht that was absolutely wonderful!  Absolutely wonderful!  So he gave me a new dimension, I suppose, on how you organise your material, because the other thing he talked about was how you do research on profoundly deaf people, you know, and all sorts of in
teresting ways of tackling this kind of thing.  But I suppose it\rquote s a matter of some regret that, because I wanted to finish the book, finish the study, I didn\rquote t feel that I could take more of his ideas \endash 
 apart from the idea of getting a good idea \endash  more into this other work, and make it more \'85 I don\rquote t know what the word is.  But that\rquote s how \'85
 the move from continuity, the Arensberg-like resistance to change in Gosforth, to this what I call \'93dynamic equilibrium\'94 in Ashworthy, because the question that one is l
eft with is, you know, how do you keep the thing going?  How does it balance?  Why is it that there is a farmer on every farm, right?  And even when you get \'85
 I remember, there was an insurance broker from Liverpool, who bought a farm, because he decided he wanted to be a farmer, and after two years he went broke.  And I thought, \'93I wonder what will happen to his farm?\'94  Because, you know, he\rquote 
s been bad news to people.  He\rquote s only been there two years.  But another farmer\rquote s son took on the farm at what was s
een as a more reasonable price.  And if a farmer dropped dead or whatever, there was always a mechanism.  And what I did was, I actually tried to establish \endash  this is what I called a \'93social field\'94 \endash 
 which is an area around Ashworthy in which this kind of \'85
 migration, internal migration, or local migration, took place.  So there were no farmers that would come from 15 miles away to buy a farm in North Lew, you see, it was too far away.  But in the four or five Parishes round about, they were all seen as par
t of the system that allowed you to move between farm and another, and so they weren\rquote t \'85 in one sense, they weren\rquote t outsiders, and this meant that the isolation, which I\rquote d thought was characteristic of Gosforth, didn\rquote 
t exist there, although there was still a \'85 quite a strong sense of local identity.  So that\rquote s how that came about.
