\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid8672334 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Gosforth less isolated, and it was interesting that John Craven\rquote s \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85 (INAUDIBLE \endash  230) comment, in this little television programme, was \'85 he said \'85 sorry, he\rquote d remarked that I\rquote 
d said, towards the end of the book, that I was worried about sort of urban/modern technological ideas represented by Sellafield, as destroying the local culture, and that he thought that I\rquote d been unduly pessimistic.  Well, I don\rquote 
t know if I was being pessimistic or not, I mean, because you\rquote d have to go back to have a look at Gosforth.  I suspect that quite a lot of the houses in Gosforth are now second homes \endash  I suspect \endash  but I\rquote ve no idea.  So I think 
\'85 insofar as I have thought about this, I think what \'85 the criticism of community studies as being sort of idiosyncratic, and not being easily fitted into general statements about family life, or rural life, whatever it is, is justified \'85
 largely justified, because I think that if I\rquote d done Gosforth with a different \'85 if I\rquote d done it the other way about, if I\rquote d done Ashworthy and then Gosforth, Gosforth wouldn\rquote t have been the same Gosforth that 
I did, because I\rquote d have been influenced by the ideas I had in Ashworthy.  And this was, I think, underlined a bit \'85
 I had an Irish student called Haughey (?? Sp), who was related to the Irish Prime Minister, Haughey, who had been in trouble for one reason or another, and he\rquote d read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Gosforth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
, and he was going to do a study of some village in Ireland, which had been studied before.  And he came to see me, and he said, \'93Which should I use \endash  Gosforth or Ashworthy \endash  to do this study?\'94  He wanted to do a sort of r
epeat of Gosforth, and I said, \'93Well, I\rquote m not sure that\rquote s the right question\'94.  I said, \'93I think you should collect the data and then think about whether either Gosforth or Ashworthy are fit\'94.  I said, \'93The one thing you mustn
\rquote t do is think in terms of Arensberg, because Arensberg has dominated rural studies in Ireland\'94, and he said \'85 so he went away.  And when he came back, it could have been written by \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85
. Arensberg!  (LAUGHS)  Yes!  It was all about the name on the land and things like this.  And, of course, if you\rquote re convinced that that\rquote s how it is, you can quite easily find data to support it \endash  I suppose.  I don\rquote 
