\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid8672334 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
No, not entirely, because I didn\rquote t use the \'85 well, I ha
d a questionnaire.  I used participant observation, and it was much more participant observation in Ashworthy, and I used interviews, lots of interviews, so in broad terms, the methodology was the same, or the methods were the same.  Where it differed, I 
think, was that I realised that I had to be much \'85 what is the word? - more scrupulous?  whatever it was \endash  in analysing the data from the interviews, which weren\rquote 
t predisposed by ideas about stability or fluidity or whatever.  I let the data, as it were, speak for themselves.  The other thing that \'85 the other difference was, which is, I think, a different point entirely.  When }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Gosforth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  was published, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
News Chronicle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  as it then was, published a series of extracts from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Gosforth}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , called \'93Roses Round the Door\'94, and they sent people to interview people in Gosforth, none of whom had read the book.  And I learnt \endash  and this was in the days of innocence 
\endash  that you have to be very careful with the British press, because the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Daily Express}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
 sent an interviewer to interview the bank manager \endash  Mr. Blair.  And Mr. Blair, like all bank managers, was very cautious, and he\rquote d said to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Daily Express
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  interviewer, \'93Well, I\rquote d rather wait until I\rquote ve seen Mr. Williams, to get his version of what the book was about.  And I want to read the book\'94
.  And the next morning, in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Daily Express}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , in a page that says, \'93Bank manager says, 
\lquote Wait till I see him\rquote \'94!  So, and a lot of people \'85 they\rquote re all anonymous, all the people are anonymous, but relatively easily identified.  I mean, Mr. Paterson, the wine merchant \endash  there\rquote 
s only one wine merchant living in Gosforth!  And when I came to do Ashworthy, I thought, \'93Well, now, I hadn\rquote t actually, perhaps, paid enough attention to what the people in the village would think of the book when it appeared, and that \'85\'94
 - this is shades, now, of all this ethical stuff that came after I did Leiston (?? \endash  299).  \'93Perhaps I should be more careful about what I write about if it causes needless harm or offence, or whatever it was\'94.  And when I actually came t
o actually analyse the material \'85
 I mean, in Gosforth, one of the things that caused deep offence, which I never anticipated, was I showed the number of children that had been born within the first nine months of marriage, which was quite a high percentage, and that \'85
 I mean, first of all, people said it was lies, and secondly they said, \'93It makes Gosforth look immoral\'94 and so forth, and it\rquote s nothing of the kind, of course!  So I thought, \'93I must be careful\'94
.  So, as a consequence of that, I left out quite a lot of material.  Sorry, go back a stage.  Gosforth \'85 Gosforth, as far as Gosforth was concerned, I sort of believed that \'85 um \'85 science or scholarship was more important than people\rquote 
s hurt feelings, although \'85 although I realised that Jefferson might be
 hurt when I said that, you know, he changed his accent and things like this, I wanted to give a true account of what life was like in Gosforth, and I thought that if people were upset, they\rquote 
re upset.  And there was a retired diplomat called Nunn, who lived in Gosforth, and I said some things that he found very hurtful, for example.  So when I went to Ashworthy, I thought, \'93I must avoid this\'94
.  And I avoided it in the sense that I used a sieve, if you like - whatever the appropriate word is - that did not use material that I thought would be very hurtful, although it seemed to me to be extremely valuable in terms of the analysis, and I
\rquote ve often wondered, since, whether \'85 I \'85 I wondered about it.  Can I give you an example?
