\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The village shop 
\endash  there were two village shops in North Lew, across the Square \endash  and one of them was run by a man called Harold Saunders, and every morning I\rquote 
d cross the Square and go in and get the newspaper from Harold Saunders, that he kept on calling \'93The Manchester Gun\'94.  But I liked Harold Saunders, he was a nice man, and we got on very well together.  Now, as I had good informants, \'85\'85\'85
\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85.. (INAUDIBLE \endash  336) good informants in Gosforth, I also had good informants in North Lew, one of whom was the
 shoemaker, again.  So I got this story from the shoemaker.  Harold Saunders was Deputy Superintendent of the Sunday School, and the Superintendent of the Sunday School was a man called George Friend \endash 
 Methodist.  It was a Methodist Sunday School, not an A
nglican one.  George Friend, who was a retired surveyor, dropped dead.  And the following evening, the Committee of the Sunday School met, and stood in memory of George Friend.  And one of the members of the Committee was George Friend\rquote 
s niece.  So they go through all the business of how sad it is, George Friend, and they come to Any Other Business.  Now, Harold Saunders, who had been Deputy Superintendent of the Sunday School for something like 30 years, thought, \'93
Now, I shall now become the Superintendent of the Sunday School\'94, and said, \'93Perhaps we should consider the vacancy for Superintendent of the Sunday School\'94.  There was a short silence, and George Friend\rquote s niece said, \'93That\rquote 
s awful!  He hasn\rquote t even been buried yet, and you\rquote re raising this issue now\'94.  So Harold Saunders realised he\rquote s made a gaffe, he said, \'93I\rquote m terribly sorry, I \'85 of course, we\rquote ll leave it till the next meeting\'94
.  Meeting ends.  The next day, individual after individual goes into Harold Saunders\rquote  shop and pays off their account \endash  because everybody had credit \endash 
 and as in Arensberg, again, credit is an expression of trust between businessmen and \'85 and client, whatever it is, so you don\rquote t pay off your account, because you have to trust each other.  These people all came in, thousands o
f them came in, paid off their account, and went to the other shop.  Right?  And I went in the next day to see Harold, and he was looking \'85 he said, \'93I\rquote ve lost half my business.  I\rquote 
ve lost half my business because I made this stupid mistake at this meeting, and I\rquote ve offended everybody\'94
, and this woman, this niece it was, had gone around telling everybody what Harold had done, and it was so offensive they decided they couldn\rquote t sort of patronise his shop any more, so they moved over to the shop \'85 was very sur
prised by this business.  Well, I thought, \'93What could be a more superb example of the way a community works, and how kinship and neighbourliness manifests itself in dealing with social order and things like that\'94.  I couldn\rquote 
t use it.  I just could not use it, because I thought, \'93If Horace sees this, it\rquote ll complete destroy him\'94, and he\rquote d already lost half his business, \'93and if I put this in print, you know, it could have ruined him\'94
, so I left it out.  And there were half a dozen, perhaps more, a dozen or so examples of this kind of thing that I found, which were \'85 you know, even if you dreamt of that, there couldn\rquote t be better examples!  But I couldn\rquote 
t use them, and I couldn\rquote t actually say I couldn\rquote t use them, so I didn\rquote t actually refer to it.  So that was one of the bigger differences between the two, I\rquote 
d lost my purity of scientific purpose by the time I came round to Ashworthy!  And I remember talking to people about this, and the anthropologists said, \'93Well, of course, if you\rquote re working with the Tiv or something like that, they\rquote 
re never going to find out, you know, because they\rquote re semi-literate or whatever.  That\rquote s a mistake, because, in fact, you know, in modern African societies, people do read these books.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Now they do, yes.

