\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
They were Mr. A and Mr. B.  Gosforth was identified.  The inhabitants weren\rquote t.  In Ashworthy, I turned that upside down.  I invented a name for the place, and I drew maps and things like this, that concealed, as far as you \'85 you\rquote 
d have to do a lot of homework to find out where it was, but I simply called Harold Smail as Harold Smail, and everyone.  But again, I mean, interestingly enough, this turned out to be a rather pointless exercise, because there was a chap called Martin 
\'85 George Martin?  Martin, who was a journalist-cum-writer who wrote about Devon, and had written a book that I\rquote d reviewed, slightly critically, as being journalistic, and he did a review of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Ashworthy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , and said, \'93Well, of course, everybody knows this is North Lew\'94!  (LAUGHS)  So that\rquote s 
about three months after the book came out.  So I\rquote d lost it anyway!  And, I mean, these days, you certainly couldn\rquote t conceal it, you know, with the modern intrusive press.  So that was a sort of fairly pointless exercise anyway.
