\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 So when you talked
 about the people in Gosforth being upset, you knew that through the \'85 newspaper interview?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
I knew it through the newspaper interview, I also knew it because \'85 you know, I\rquote d come to know a lot of people in Gosforth.  I\rquote d left by then, I was in Keele.  But through my wife\rquote s family, they \'85
 they knew that these people had been hurt.  There was quite a lot in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Whitehaven News}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
 about it, and people were ringing the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Whitehaven News}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  and said, \'93This chap\rquote 
s telling lies about us\'94, and things like this, and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Whitehaven News}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
 would print articles saying, \'93Welshman tells lies about English Parish\'94, or whatever it was!  But most of it was sort of grapevine stuff, that people were hurt.  And Will Wilson, the Headmaster, told us quite a lot about things.  And a lot of it 
\'85 the other thing I suppose I learnt was that, with the Horace Saunders story, you could say, \'93Well, self-evidently, this would be hurtful to someone like Horace, or, indeed, the people who\rquote d done it\'94
.  But a number of the things in Gosforth that completely surprised me, completely surprised me, which people took offence to \'85 absolutely \'85 an example.  An example \'85 and you\rquote re going to say, \'93Oh, just being na\'efve\'94
.  But in those days, farmers in Gosforth wore clogs.  I mean, real sound wooden clogs
.  A very sensible thing to wear on heavy soils in Gosforth, and they will last forever.  So I put in the chapter on farming, that farmers wear clogs.  And this caused profound offence, because people said that what I was doing, I was poking fun of them a
s
 if they were peasants.  Only peasants wear clogs, right?  And that caused as much offence as the thing about premarital pregnancies.  Now, there are a number of things like that where it never ever occurred to me that it might offend people.  And, of cou
rse, what this shows is, first of all, how unperceptive I was, but also that I didn\rquote t actually understand, sufficiently, the values that drive the society.  In some things, I \'85
 from my Welsh Sabbatarian background, I could see that some things would be offensive and other not.  What I couldn\rquote t see was that the very notion of an outsider coming to study the village, and misleading them by saying it was a history \endash 
 because they forgot the bit about modern life, quite understandably!  You should be suspicious o
f this chap deceiving us, and saying things about it that the outside world would find funny.  I mean, another one which was less offensive, but a number of people objected to, was that what farmers did with calves once they\rquote d done \'85 \'85\'85
\'85\'85\'85\'85.. (INAUDIBLE \endash  463) feed them first, and then put them in pens, and then put them out in the fields.  Well, they thought that pen feeding was an old-fashioned \'85
 some of them thought that pen-feeding was an old-fashioned way of rearing calves, and that this was, in a sense, pointing out that they were behind the times and so on.  But I didn\rquote t know enough about calving, really, to know \'85
 I just recorded it, because I thought, \'93This tells you how it was\'94.  And there were lots and lots of examples like that, that filtered through eventually.  It didn\rquote t happen, I don\rquote t think \endash 
 well, if it did happen in North Lew, it didn\rquote t come back to me \endash  because the shoemaker there wrote to me, we kept in touch for quite a long time afterwards, and I said, \'93Were people upset?\'94 and so forth, and he said, \'93
No, no.  As far as I know, people are not all that upset.  One or two are a bit upset they\rquote re in the book at all\'94, sort of thing, \'93But you didn\rquote t say anything that they regarded as \'85\'94
  I mean, some of the things that I did wonder might cause offence, but I couldn\rquote t see how to avoid it, was that the gap between Methodists and Anglicans, in this village, was very profound.  Very profound \'85
 in the way they behaved from day to day.  Now, Methodists never went into the pub, ever.  They never went into the pub.  And so if you went into the pub, you knew that everybody there was an Anglican, or whatever \endash  not a Methodist.  So I thought, 
\'93Well, I wonder if they go into Okehampton to buy their beer?\'94  And what they did was, they went round to the back door of the pub, and Mr. Werdon, the landlord, would have their regular order, which he\rquote 
d sell them at the back door, so they didn\rquote t need to come into the pub!  Well \'85 so I actually said this in the book, and no one found it offensive at all.
