\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Not at all.  Now, that I was hesitant about putting it in, because I thought, \'93Well, you know, does this sound hypocritical, or whatever it was?\'94  But no one objected to that.  And the other thing I remember about \'85 I\rquote m sort of ranging fai
rly widely was \'85 in Gosforth, I was so \'85 well, I was younger, a young post-graduate, I was so convinced of the rightness of my cause, I hardly ever thought about what was the right thing to do.  But it wasn\rquote t like that in \'85
 in Ashworthy, because I joined the Victoria Social Club, which was a young men\rquote s Social Club, and I used to go there regularly, two or three nights a week, to play darts or play snooker.  And I wasn\rquote 
t a very good darts player, and I used to get beaten regularly, and bought lots of pints of beer as a result of this, but I thought, \'93That\rquote s good for you to practice!\'94  But I was playing \'85
 I used to play snooker, I was quite a good snooker player, and one evening I was playing with someone, and this farmer\rquote s son came in, he was a very stroppy young man, and \'85 erm \'85 sort of had poked fun at me rather a lot, and he said, \'93
Do you want a game of snooker?\'94  So I said, \'93Okay\'94.  So he said, \'93Ten shillings on it\'94, which was a lot of money in those days.  So I said, \'93No, no, I don\rquote t \'85\'94  \'93Oh, you\rquote re frightened, are you?  You\rquote 
re frightened\'94.  \'93A pound\'94, he said, \'93A pound\'94.  And by this time, the Social Club, which was quite big, was quiet.  Right?  He said, \'93Come on.  Show you\rquote re not a coward\'94.  So I said, \'93Right\'94.  So I knew, because I
\rquote d seen this boy playing before, that I could beat the pants off him, without any effort at all.  Then I had to think, \'93If I lose, which I could do, I think, fairly convincingly, will people think, you know, \lquote This stranger \'85\rquote 
\'94 \endash  this was early on in the fieldwork \endash  \'93\rquote is not much good\rquote .  And if I beat him, will this cause offence?  Because this is the outsider coming in, the sort of hustler!\'94  And I\rquote m playing along, and it\rquote 
s sort of fairly even Stephen, because I\rquote m not trying very hard, and I can\rquote t make up my mind.  And then he said something which offended me \endash  I can\rquote t remember what it was (LAUGHS) \endash 
 offended me.  I put up with it.  He did this three or four times, and I thought, \'93Right.  I\rquote m not putting up with this\'94.  So I just sort of finished the game, and beat him handsome
ly.  And he handed the pound over, and marched out, and I sort of looked about, and everybody was sort of sitting there looking at me, and I thought, \'93I\rquote ve really blown it now\'94
, you know!  The fieldworker, a real disaster!  A chap got up and said, \'93We\rquote ve been waiting for that to happen for years!\'94  (LAUGHS)  So, I mean, for no sort of rational reason at all, I\rquote 
d done the right thing without realising it.  But it then made me think about, systematically, about the role of outsider doing research of this kind, and there\rquote d been a \'85 an interesting example of that when I arrived, which I didn\rquote 
t note.  I had a Morris Minor coupe, with a hood, which I put down.  And the first day I arrived, I thought, \'93I will drive around the village and the farms\'94, just to give my
self some idea of the place.  So I drove around, and went back to the Green Dragon, and I didn\rquote t see a soul.  Not a soul.  And I thought, \'93Well, that was quite useful\'94
.  And then in the evening, I was sitting in the pub, and someone came in and said, \'93I saw you this morning, in the blue car, the one with the hood down\'94.  And I said, \'93Oh yes\'94.  So I thought, \'93I\rquote ll make a note of who saw me\'94
.  And I counted up, and over the next three or four days, 32 people had seen me driving around in my car, and identified me not only as a stranger, but a stranger who\rquote 
s staying with Bill Werdon in the Green Dragon, and had come to do some kind of study.  So I thought, \'93The lesson of this is, that you are observed \'85\'94
