\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Yes.  Yes.  And because of that, I mean, beating this young man at snooker, could guarantee that the news would get around before the next day, how, whatever I did - and this business of going to the Metho
dist Chapel and going to the Anglican Church on alternate Sundays, right - and then occasionally \'85 I was doing this from Keele, I\rquote d go back at the weekend to Keele, and people would say, \'93
You were supposed to go to the church last Sunday.  Didn\rquote t see you there\'94, you know!  (LAUGHS)  And if there were funerals, I went to every funeral.  And I went to weddings, but mostly funerals.  \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. (INAUDIBLE 
\endash  007), because funerals were, as in South Wales, occasions where kindred, friends, neighbours, workmates, attend as a matter of respect to the person who died.  And I didn\rquote 
t fit any of these characters.  I might just as well have been the reporter from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Western Evening News}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , so one of the difficulties that that caused me was, should I actually write down \endash  as I did in Gosforth \endash 
 the names of everybody who attended the funeral?  Would that seem even more intrusive?  So I had to agonise.  And, I mean, you can\rquote t look up a book to tell you answers to questions like this.  So the first time, I decided I wouldn\rquote t,
 I wouldn\rquote t make notes.  And I went to see the shoemaker, and I said, \'93I noticed you were at the funeral, Harold.  I\rquote d dearly love to have known, you know, who was there, but I didn\rquote t want to make notes.\'94  \'93Oh\'94, he said, 
\'93I\rquote ll tell you.  Get your book out\'94.  (LAUGHS)  And went through them all!  He said, \'93They wouldn\rquote t mind next time\'94, said they wouldn\rquote t mind, he said, \'93They expect you to do something like that\'94
.  So thereafter, I used his advice when I was asking, you know, about things, whether to record things or \'85 whether to ask people explicit questions about things.  It wasn\rquote t always right, at least, it didn\rquote 
t always have the desired effect, but, I mean, it was a use of the good informant as hadn\rquote t occurred to me before.  And when you look at the anthr
opological literature, I mean, serious anthropologists do this all the time.  You know, they use the key informant as a guide to the proprieties of the society in which they\rquote re working.  So the only time \'85 I mean, as far as I\rquote 
m aware, there are a number of textbooks aren\rquote t there, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The Craft of Social Anthropology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , and so on, and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Community Studies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
, which tell you a lot of this, but I don\rquote t think there is a systematic account which actually addresses \endash  perhaps there is, perhaps there is since I\rquote ve retired \endash  wh
ich addresses these sorts of issues that gives you advice.  And when I went to Swansea, I \'85 in the second year, I did a course called, \'93Community Studies\'94, which was compulsory, I have to say!  Well, what I did was, for the first term, was \'85
 no notes, I si
mply sat down and talked to them about how you do Gosforth, how you do Ashworthy, what sort of results you get, why you should be sceptical about some of them, what value they have in terms of generalisations and things like that, and I enjoyed that, and 
I think the students enjoyed it because \'85 like this Harold Saunders story, for example, it\rquote s the sort of thing that people can understand quite readily.  The other thing I remember about George Friend \endash  this is the man who died \endash 
 was \'85 I went into the shop one Sunday, to get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The Observer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
, I think it was, and George Friend was passing, and he said, \'93Good afternoon, Mr. Williams\'94, \'93Good afternoon\'94.  He said, \'93You\rquote ve got a Sunday paper there\'94.  I said, \'93Yes\'94.  He said, \'93You shouldn\rquote 
t read a Sunday paper, you know, it\rquote s not proper to read papers on a Sunday\'94.  I said, \'93Oh, right.  Right!\'94
  So he went off, shaking his head, and that sort of chance remark made me wonder, in fact, how widespread this was.  I mean, was it true that all Methodists didn\rquote t read papers o
n Sunday?  Now that was a chance encounter and a chance remark.  So I asked Harold how many of his customers, who were Methodists, bought Sunday papers.  And Harold said, \'93Oh, I\rquote ve no idea.  I\rquote ve no idea\'94.  I said, \'93Come on, Harold!
\'94  \'93No, I\rquote ve absolutely no idea\'94, and clearly Harold realised that this is something he shouldn\rquote t tell me!  (LAUGHS)  So the only way I could find out, if I\rquote d wanted to, and I didn\rquote 
t pursue it, was to sit in my room in the pub, looking down on the Square, and looking who went in and out on a Sunday.  But I couldn\rquote t be bothered doing that, and it wasn\rquote t worth it.  So there is a strong \'85 I mean, it\rquote 
s not like a survey, as it were, where you take a random sample or whatever, and you work your way through to achieve sample.  So much o
f it, it seems to me, is, as with anthropology, anthropological studies, is fortuitous, you have a fortuitous encounter which leads to something, and that leads to something else, and, therefore, the good anthropologist is, perhaps, someone who can take a
dvantage of these fortuitous encounters, and I mean, I thought I was quite a good fieldworker, I must say.  I thought that \'85
 the other thing I learnt, and, I mean, this is banal, was simply to sit and listen, because I discovered quite quickly, even in Gosforth, that if you simply, \'93Mmm\'94
, and you show interest, people will go on talking, and they will say things that they hadn\rquote t actually intended to say \endash  without being asked questions.  I mean, if you ask questions, you might interrupt the flow, and you make them think, 
\'93Why is he asking that?\'94 whereas if I sat \'85 and out it would come.  But again, I don\rquote t think the textbooks tell you much about that really.
