\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Sceptical, I think.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Yeah, sceptical.  Sceptical.  Erm \'85 I\rquote m not sure I \'85
 I think this is related, in an indirect way, to the thing that puzzled me at the time, puzzled me up to a point, about anthropological, you know, traditional anthropological fieldwork, which is based on learning a language, like going to live in a villag
e and speaking to people in the language.  Now, however good a linguist you are, there must be whole areas of life where you don\rquote 
t have access simply because your comprehension of the language is limited, or, more importantly, your comprehension of the \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. (INAUDIBLE \endash  069) conceptual apparatus that underlies the language, isn\rquote t 
\'85 I mean, I knew that, but I don\rquote t think I realised how applicable that was, in a sense, to studying a village where you share the language, that even if you share the language, it doesn\rquote 
t necessarily follow that the same words mean the same thing to you, that they meant, and in my case, as a Welshman, people \'85 in both these places, using words that I\rquote d \'85 like my Sabbatarianism business, going into the pub, using words that h
ave subtly different meanings, so that, perhaps \'85 a sort of note of scepticism about what one is doing in interpreting these things is essential.  I don\rquote t know.  I mean, I find this here, in the village.  I\rquote 
m by no means the anthropologist studying the village, because I\rquote m part of it, and I see myself as part of it, but very occasionally, something is said which \endash  I can\rquote t think of an example offhand \endash 
 that causes my surprise.  And then I realise that, in fact, I\rquote ve misinterpreted what\rquote s said, because my use of a particular phrase, or a set of words, might be different from the way they\rquote 
re used here.  Or occasionally, one comes across something that is not expected.  I mean, for example, about two years ago I was in the pub, because \'85 after we bell-ring practi
ce, we go into the pub for a drink, and that used to be on a Thursday, and we went in this particular Thursday, and there were two well-established local residents, and they were engaged in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f42\fs22\ul\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  most virulent anti-Semitism that I\rquote ve heard for years.  I mean, you wouldn\rquote 
t see it in the newspaper or on the BBC, because it was really really unpleasant.  And it came as a terrible shock to me.  And afterwards, when I thought about it, I thought, \'93Well, it\rquote s partly a shock because it\rquote 
s unfamiliar, you know, you don\rquote t encounter it very often - it\rquote s not the sort of thing that you would encounter in a university, for example, or on the radio \endash  but it was also a shock because I think, somewhere or other, I\rquote 
d assumed that the people here didn\rquote t engage in that kind of discourse.  You know, that it didn\rquote t fit the notion of Norfolk rural life, as being tolerant and things like that.  Well, that, I think, applies \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85
. (INAUDIBLE \endash  096) to fieldwork, actually, that there are hidden \endash  it\rquote s an obvious point, isn\rquote t it \endash  hidden agendas.  I don\rquote t think I\rquote m post-modernist about this!  So \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
And then what about the other point you made about generalisability from one or two studies, how do you feel about that now?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Well, I think \'85
 oh, sorry!  I think if you wanted to make general statements about, let\rquote 
s say, English rural life, that doing a survey, you get a million pounds from the ESRC, you do a survey of English farming and values and things like this, would give you a lot of valuable information, but it wouldn\rquote 
t actually get at the kind of things like Boulton and his tatie digger, because surveys can\rquote 
t uncover that kind of thing.  But set against that, the question is, if you read a whole series of community studies, is it possible, or plausible, to say, \'93Well, it\rquote s like that in Gosforth, or Ashworthy, it\rquote 
s like that in the Cheviots, it\rquote s like that in somewhere else, and it\rquote s like that in somewhere else, so the likelihood is that here is a common theme\'94.  Now, I think if it were rigorous, you would say, \'93That\rquote s p
robably going beyond the evidence\'94
.  And yet the thing that used to strike me, in reading these studies, was that some particular incident or observation of something would strike me as immediately true when I saw it.  I can give you an example of that.  J
immy Littlejohn, in his book, says that there\rquote s a shepherd sitting in front of the fire with his family, and they\rquote re sitting in complete silence.  And then he says, after about three-quarters of an hour, \'93Oh aye, I am\'94
.  Right?  And then there\rquote s more silence.  And Jimmy says, \'93What that is saying to his family is, \lquote Well, everything\rquote s fine, isn\rquote t it.  The world\rquote s okay, and I don\rquote t need to spell it out.  But that\rquote 
s how it is\rquote \'94.  And when I read that, I thought, \'93Yes, that\rquote s how it is, because that\rquote s how people in Cumbria behave!\'94 they don\rquote t feel it necessary to talk all the time.  You know, they sit in companionable silence.  
\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85 (INAUDIBLE \endash  121), you know, that you go into a village, and it\rquote s the same here.  People don\rquote t talk all the time.  Maybe they talk all the time \'85
\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85 (INAUDIBLE \endash  123), but companionable silence is a real aspect of English rural life.  It is \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85. (INAUDIBLE \endash  124).  It\rquote 
s not an aspect of South Wales working-class industrial life, I may tell you!  People talk all the time!  And seeing that, I thought, \'93
Well, this is something that probably if someone else did a community study somewhere else, they would notice the same thing\'94.  So there may be \'85 it\rquote s not a very important \'85 strands, that one can draw out in u
nderstanding the fabric of these people\rquote s lives.  And that\rquote s about as far as I\rquote d go on generalisations, I think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Now, about Keele, your time at Keele, I was just thinking about what you were teaching there, because you were in Geography, but I think you were teaching Community Studies, is that right?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid12279015 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 I \'85 I \'85 went 
\'85 I was appointed to Keele to teach Historical Geography, because that was my legacy from Emrys Bowen, and I actually taught a course that was as much Archaeology as it was Histor
ical Geography.  And in those days, Keele had, Lindsay had his Foundation Year, which started with the origins of the earth, and finished with the atomic bomb.  And I was asked to give ten lectures on pre-history, which I did.  So that my first teaching a
ssignment, if you like, in the Geography Department, was a very Aberystwyth kind of Archaeology-cum-Human Geography.  And the other members of staff taught traditional things \endash  Geomorphology (?? \endash 
 141) and the like.  And then after four or five years, we needed new options, and I said to my boss I thought I could teach a course on Communities.  And he said, \'93Well, you can\rquote t call it that, you\rquote ve got to call it something else\'94
.  So I said, \'93Well, let\rquote s call it Social Geography\'94, because the term was now commonplace.  So I taught something called \'93Social Geography\'94
.  But in order to give it some kind of perceived relevance to a degree in geography, I had to put some other stuff in, and there\rquote s a group of French \'85 sort of these new geographers, that paid a lot of attention to social \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85
\'85\'85 (INAUDIBLE \endash  149), so I put those in as well, and called it \'93Social Geography\'94.  And I knew, at the point, actually, that I was going to write a textbook, for Longmans, on Social Geography.  But I got a sabbatical and decided I
\rquote d take the sabbatical, and then I got the job in Swansea, and it sort of fell through.  So \'85 so that\rquote s how that came.  Of course, when I was interviewed in \'85 I actually applied \'85 when I was in Swansea, I \'85
 when I was in Keele, I applied for Geography jobs as well, because I thought my chances of getting a Chair in Geography are greater if I\rquote m seen in a Geography Department.  But I \'85
 I only got short-listed once, I think, because I was far too radical, with the orthodoxies of the time.  And the Swansea job was the first one that came up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10757096 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
And about Keele, I mean, Keele was quite an experimental university at that time, wasn\rquote t it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10757096 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
It was.  I went when it was a year old.  I think?  A year old.  And it had 400 students.  Lovely!  And there were
 no Single Honours, everybody did Joint Honours at least, and you had to do, if you were Arts, you had to do a Science subsidiary, and if you were Science, you had to do an Arts subsidiary.  And so there was this \'85
 you had to pass the Foundation Year before you could move into the second \'85 it was a four-year course, which, I think, was revolutionary then.  Well, for England, anyway.  And I enjoyed it.  I mean, it \'85
 you know, you had students doing things like Chemistry and English, let\rquote s say, and Geography you could combine with anything, because there were no artificial constraints.  Constraints \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85
.. (INAUDIBLE \endash  169) turned out to be timetable constraints in the end, that you can\rquote t do every \'85 combine everything with everything, and then fit into the timetable, because you used to start at eight o\rquote 
clock in the morning, and finish at seven at night, even to \'85 you know, do the existing things.  So, yes, it was \'85 Lindsay died a year after I got there, and we had a series of new Principals, who only
 lasted about two or three years, all of whom had different ideas.  You couldn\rquote t do a higher degree.  If you wanted to do a Ph.D., you had to do it in Birmingham, Oxford or London, I think.  It didn\rquote 
t have a degree, high degree granting status until \'85 I would think I was there about seven years.
