Yes.  There was a philosopher called Alan Montefiori (?? Sp) who went to Balliol, and he and I did a series of seminars on \'93Determinsim and Possibilism\'94
 as we called it, and wrote a couple of papers.  So we saw a lot of each other.  There was a historian called Paul Coves, he was an expert on 12}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\super\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  century Italy or something like that, and the three of us had sort of fairly intellectual conversations about our disciplines.  I don\rquote 
t think any of the professors were particularly influential, that I can think of.  I suppose Bryce Galli\'85\'85\'85\'85.. (?? \endash  187) was.  Oh \'85
 Sammy Feiner, the political scientist, I admired, and I read nearly everything he wrote, out of intellectual interest rather than direct influence on my work.  No, I don\rquote t \'85 I can\rquote t think of anyone else, offhand.
