\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10757096 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
No.  No.  No.  No, that came in Swansea.  I just did two courses in Keele \endash  the historical \'85 Archaeology/Historica
l Geography Course, and then the sort of Community/Social Geography course.  They were very popular options, and I did a lot of teaching actually, and I supervised some Ph.D. students.  But, of course, when I went to Swansea, there was no Sociology, and t
h
e Chairman of Sociology and Anthropology was the first of its kind, and there were no courses, no Department, no students, it was absolutely start from scratch, which was a nice situation to be in.  And the first thing I discovered was that, Swansea, like
 most universities, was centred on the notion of the Single Honours Degree.  That was the perfect artefact.  And we had to establish a new Faculty, and I became the \'85
 after the first nine months, the first Dean of the Faculty.  So I put a paper to the Facul
ty, saying that we should have no Single Honours Degrees, they should all be Joint Honours, and putting a Keele type argument for it.  Now, the way it worked in Swansea was that \endash  and still does \endash 
 a Department like Psychology could be in Arts, Science and Social Sciences, so you could do a B.Sc. in Psychology, which was largely experimental \'85
 for a B.Sc..  Or you could do a BA in Psychology, Social Psychology, this sort of stuff.  Or you could do ours, which was a sort of mixture.  But they were all Single Honours Degrees.  So when I came, I said, \'93No, no, you can\rquote 
t do Psychology as a Single Honours Degree in our Faculty, you have to do it with something\'94, and then that created a whole series of very popular combinations \endash  Psychology/Sociology;  Psychology/A
nthropology;  Psychology/Statistics, and things like that.  And for the first 15 years, I suppose, you couldn\rquote 
t do a Single Honours, in our Faculty, in anything.  And then there was pressure from some of the staff, and from the students, to introduce Single Honours courses, which I resisted, but it didn\rquote 
t work.  They started becoming introduced.  The only nice thing about it was \endash  and I thought this would kill off the Joint Honours, of course it didn\rquote t \endash  if people wanted to do Single Honours, they\rquote d go into
 the Humanities or Science, for the most part.  If they wanted to do a Joint Degree, they\rquote d come into our Faculty.  So I imported Lindsay\rquote 
s idea of a sort of wider education.  I tried to persuade Swansea to have something like the Foundation Year, that was far far too radical for them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10757096 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
And what about your vision of Sociology and Anthropology as \'85 I mean, if you\rquote re starting a new Department, what was your vision for that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10757096 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Well \'85
 I saw myself as an anthropologist, to start with, and I\rquote d read far more \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85(INAUDIBLE \endash  225) and Malinowsky than I\rquote 
d read Durkheim and Weber and people like this, so I saw myself as an anthropologist, and my interest in community studies fitted with that.  But I realised that we would need two sort of streams \endash  one Anthropology, one Sociology \endash 
 with some joint courses.  And so I appointed people like Chris Harris, who was unmistakeably a sociologist, although he\rquote d worked with Colin Rosser.  And I appointed people like Maurice Bloch, who\rquote s now a Professor at LSE, who\rquote 
s unmistakeably an anthropologist \endash  Madagascar.  And the vision was that we could exist side by side, but come together in terms of theory and methodology.  But it was too difficult.  It was too difficult in the sense of being teachable to unde
rgraduates, I think.  It was asking too much of them to try to take two bodies of knowledge, and incorporate them into a sort of whole.  So, in the first year, you had to do eight subjects \'85
 the nearer I could get to the Foundation was that having an eight subject first year is not.  Of those eight subjects, if you wanted to do Sociology, you had to do Anthropology, and vice-versa.  You couldn\rquote 
t do Sociology with Economics or whatever.  But you could do two courses of Sociology \'85 so you could do two courses in Economics, two courses in Psychology, two courses in Statistics, so you\rquote d end up doing four subjects, let\rquote 
s say.  In Sociology and Anthropology you couldn\rquote t do that.  If you wanted to do two courses in Sociology, you still had to do a course in Anthrop
ology.  And they were taught as if they were very closely related to each other.  At the end of the first year, you didn\rquote 
t have to do Sociology and Anthropology, you could do Sociology and Psychology, or Anthropology and whatever it was.  But the substanti
al proportion of the students actually did Sociology and Anthropology.  A majority did Sociology and Anthropology together, because they saw them as related.  I think they also saw fairly mundane advantages in being taught by the same people, as it were. 
 So \'85 and that lasted \'85
 and I think, in the end, very very reluctantly, we started moving towards a Single Honours course.  And when I gave up, to become Professor of Social Policy, we appointed Reg Byron as my successor, as Professor of Sociology and Anthr
opology, and he made the separation quite explicit.  I mean, he saw himself as an anthropologist, and he developed Anthropology, and appointed anthropologists.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10757096 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
He worked on Scottish fishing communities, as well, didn\rquote t he?
