\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10757096 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 That\rquote 
s right.  Yes, that\rquote s the chap.  And he\rquote s still there.  He\rquote s been ill, I think, but he\rquote s still there.  So \'85 I mean, insofar as \'85 I don\rquote t know whether you\rquote 
d call it a vision, but my feeling was that everything I\rquote d read, as an undergraduate, and then as a post-graduate \endash  I mean, I read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
The Division of Labour in Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , for example, and I read quite a lot of Weber, I thought Weber was great.  I didn\rquote 
t see this as separable from reading Radcliffe-Brown or whatever it was, I thought I could accommodate them within the sa
me thing, and that we would require students to do the same.  It did cause substantial problems in the actual organisation of the degree, because I believed that, in fact, you should give students as much choice as possible.  I didn\rquote 
t like the idea of too 
many compulsory courses.  So, in the second year, and particularly in the third year, there was a wider choice of options.  But that created all sorts of logistic and intellectual problems, because John Parker, for example, wanted an option called \'93
The Sociology of Art\'94, which was difficult.  I mean, a very very theoretical sociologist, he taught \'93The Sociology of Art\'94.  And Margaret Canard (?? \endash  282) taught, \'93The Anthropology of the Greek Islands\'94
, okay?  Traditional anthropology.  Very hard to marry up Th
e Sociology of Art and The Anthropology of the Greek Islands, because the bridges between them were pretty exiguous! So we had, in our minds, a kind of desirable set of combinations, and a less desirable.  But since people could choose their own courses, 
we could say to them, \'93You know, you want to think carefully about this.  But if that\rquote s what you want to do, you can do it  And the vast majority of them played safe and did \'85
 I mean, I had a course on Sociological Theory, which Chris Harris taught, which I thought was exceptionally difficult, actually, but, you know \'85
 I mean, he taught it very well.  And there were courses on Anthropological Theory.  And the bright students could join the two up, but the less bright students found it difficult.  So \'85 and, o
f course, although it was the first Chair in the country, it was succeeded by a whole lot of Chairs, if not Joint Chairs, where you had Sociology and Anthropology in the same School, or whatever it was, unlike \'85
 I mean, when I was appointed in Swansea, Anthropology was an entirely separate discipline, and mainly post-graduate, and there weren\rquote t very \'85 I think only two \'85
 two, possibly three, sociology degrees in Britain, in 1963.  LSE was one, Liverpool, it was called \'93Social Science\'94, \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85.. (INAUDIBLE \endash 
 301) was another.  I think Sheffield had a degree.  And within two or three years of my being appointed, they were everywhere!  (LAUGHS)  So \'85 and they were really all Sociology Departments, I mean, Anthropology didn\rquote 
t expand anywhere near as rapidly.  But then, in fact, in Essex \'85
