\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10757096 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Well, a very Welsh thing.  My closest colleague was Daniel Williams, Professor of History, now Sir Daniel Williams.  He\rquote 
d gone to the Carmather School, he was sort of six years ahead of me, so he was a Merthyr boy, and had become Professor of History.  Very very distinguished mediaeval Welsh historian.  And Dan and I became friends.  And we featured very 
prominently, I think, in academic politics, because we always sat beside each other in Senate, two seats on the right-hand end of the Senate, in the Senate Room, and we acted together without thinking, you know, we sort of thought alike, and we used to ma
ke life very difficult for the Principals.  And no one would sit in these two seats.  If we were late, the two seats would be left empty until we arrived!  (LAUGHS)  So Dan and I \'85 um \'85
 had come from the same, you know, he came from a working-class family and all this, and we had the same values, I think, about what university education should be about \'85 same generation.  So we were \'85 we were known as \'93
Williams of fact, and Williams of fiction\'94, without actually saying which was which!  (LAUGHS)
