\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid13114403 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Yes, I did.  I \'85
 after I\rquote d been there some years, Wales got the Welsh Office, and we didn\rquote 
t have a - this seems a long time ago - but Wales had a Welsh Office, and a Secretary of State for Wales, which was regarded as an exceptionally radical step, and no one quite knew how it wor
ked.  And the First Secretary of State was a man called James Griffiths, whose brother was the very famous actor.  And James decided he would establish the Welsh Council, to give him advice.  And they wanted a sociologist, or they wanted someone that coul
d talk about social affairs, and I was the only Professor of Sociology in the University of Wales at the time, it was before Paul Almott (?? \endash 
 363) went to Cardiff.  So he asked me if I would sit on the Welsh Council, and I had a number of excellent credentials \endash 
 I was a Merthyr boy, and I was a graduate of the University of Wales in Aberystwyth, which not all the professors were, although most of them were.  So I sat on the Welsh Council for about 12 years, and this gave me an insight into \'85 you\rquote 
d call it high politics in Wales, I suppose.  And that led to my being offered the Chairmanship of the Health Authority, when the Health Authorities were established in \rquote 
74, which I took, although I had difficulty in persuading the then Principal to let me have leave of absence.  It was paid, moreover, but the money had to be handed into the University, I wasn\rquote t allowed to keep it \'85
 for a long time, but eventually I got it.  So I then \'85 and the Welsh Office told me, untruthfully, that it would be one or two days a month.  And, in fact, since it was an entirely new Organisation, it was about three days a week.  And I didn\rquote 
t give up any teaching, I moved all my teaching, and I did quite a lot of teaching, because I love teaching, into two days, and I would spend those da
ys in the University, teaching, and became heavily involved in the Health Authority and thoroughly enjoyed it.  But it also allowed me, of course, to persuade clinicians and other professionals in the Health Service, to establish close relationships with 
the University.  And the curious thing about this was that Swansea University is, literally, next door to Singleton (?? \endash 
 388) Hospital, which was a brand new hospital.  Literally next door.  So I decided that I would give a supper for the Senior Consultant
s, in the University, and I invited the Principal, as he then was, and Deans of Faculties.  And I was sitting next to Sam Richmond (?? \endash  393), who was the Senior Surgeon, and Sam said to me, \'93This is the first time I\rquote 
ve ever been invited to anything in the University\'94.  And I thought, \'93Well, that shows \'85\'94
 you know.  So from then on, all sorts of joint projects developed, and we started doing courses for health visitors, midwives, people like that.  So I felt that it had that dimension to it, and, I mean, th
e University were very understanding, because they were \endash 
 and so were my colleagues.  There were some weeks when if things were difficult in the Health Service, if we had a strike for example, in one of the hospitals, over private patients, and I just spen
t my time hurtling from one meeting to another, and I just had to say to the University, \'93Well, carry on without me\'94.  So \'85 and then \'85
