Yes, I do.  The other thing I actually feel very strongly about was being an academic being an advantage, because I had a team of Senior Officers \endash  Chief Administrators as they were called in those days \endash 
 Director of Finance, Chief Nursing Officer, Chief Medical Officer.  I used to have meetings with these people once or twice a week, and they would produce papers, policy papers, and I would say, \'93I don\rquote 
t want a single option, I want you to offer alternatives\'94, and things like this.  And then we\rquote d go through, I\rquote d go through these, and sort of ask questions and so forth.  I remember, the thing that pleased me enormously, that after the 
\'85 the Director of Finance was a young man, they appointed him when he was in his early thirties, very good.  At the end of the meeting, he said, \'93Do you know the thing I\rquote ve learnt since I\rquote ve been here?\'94 he said, \'93
Is how to analyse problems properly\'94.  He said, \'93What you obviously do in a university is, you take a problem, you analyse it, and you\rquote ve got some means of doing it.  It never occurred to me to do this in looking at policy issues, so we now 
\'85\'94  And the others said, \'93Yes, that\rquote s right\'94.  And they changed their style.  They just changed their style.  What \'85 I mean, there was a subtext of political necessity and things 
like this, nevertheless they sort of tried to use some external objectivity in solving problems.  And I would give anthropological examples, actually, to them, and say, \'93Now, look, you know, if this was a hospital in St.Mawes\'94 (?? \endash 
 433), or something like that.  But yes, it was, it was much a general thing of being an academic, I think.  And, of course, the great advantage that I had was that although it was a political appointment, I had no constituency, so I didn\rquote 
t have to worry, looking over my shoulder about a constituency, and if the Secretary of State didn\rquote t like it, he could sack me, or, at least, not reappointment me.  So I must have been doing things right, because I lasted for 17 years!
