\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid6584740 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 I was \'85
 I have a nice record.  I was the \'85 when I was appointed, in \rquote 63, I was the y
oungest professor to be appointed in Swansea, and when I was appointed to be Professor of Social Policy, I was the oldest professor to be appointed, because I was 65!  (LAUGHS)  And this was a mistake.  It was clearly a mistake, because we\rquote 
d had Social Policy, and it had simply collapsed, it wasn\rquote t attractive and things like this, and it was an offshoot of Social Work.  Didn\rquote t have enough students.  So when the Professor left, he wasn\rquote 
t reappointed, so we had an established Chair in Social Policy, which was vacant, and it was going to be vacant forever.  And it occurred to me that we really ought to be doing something about this, because I wasn\rquote 
t the only one working in public life, in the University, but we should have a Social Policy degree, and that peopl
e like myself could teach on it.  I could teach Health Policy, the Professor of Economics could teach Economic Policy and things like this, so \'85
 so I wrote a paper, saying that I thought that the University should revive the teaching of Social Policy.  And they said, \'93Absolutely splendid idea.  You can do it\'94.  So I said, \'93Okay\'94
.  I thought it time that they had fresh blood in Sociology and Anthropology, so I resigned from my Chair, and told the staff, who were sort of taken aback, and then became, the same day, Professor of Social Policy \endash 
 without a Department.  So I started again from scratch, establishing a Department.  In two years of that, I got the degree going, took over the responsibility for Social Work, which was dying, and used my Welsh connection
s to jazz it up a bit.  And I quite enjoyed that.  I mean, I didn\rquote t have to prepare any lectures, I just had to go and talk to the Health Service, and about, you know, how policy is made \endash 
 not what the textbooks tell you, but how policy is made \endash  the fact that \'85 I can remember \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85\'85 festinniog (?? \endash  540), which is in the middle of nowhere in North Wales, had a maudling (?? \endash 
 543) Health Centre, and they\rquote d been asking, for years, to have a new Health Centre.  And suddenly, the Secretary of State says th
ey can have a new Health Centre.  One might think that this was a rational response to improve facilities.  Nothing of the kind.  It was a marginal seat, right?  It was a marginal seat, and Labour thought they could probably get it if they put in a new He
alth Centre.  So they put in a new Health Centre and, sure enough, they stole it from the Lib Dems, or whatever it was.  A lot of politics.  We know, don\rquote t we, but, I mean, the books don\rquote 
t tell you that there are sort of fortuitous considerations.  So I did a lot of teaching in those terms, and produced a lot of disillusioned students as a consequence!  And \'85 by that time, I\rquote d actually \'85 I\rquote 
d stopped being Chairman of the Health Authority.  Yes, I had stopped being Chairman of the Health Authority, which was useful, because I didn\rquote 
t feel that I had to be careful about what I said, you know, in teaching.  So I did two years.  And I also, in those two years, became a Senior Vice-Principal, because I\rquote d always used being Chairman of the Health Authority as an excu
se for not becoming what we now call \'93Pro-Vice-Chancellor\'94.  And the minute I gave up being Chairman of the Health Authority, the Principal said, \'93Right, you\rquote d better be a Vice-Principal!\'94
  So I spent the last two years being a mixture of bureaucracy and teaching the discipline.  And that was quite enjoyable.
