Yes, well a series of accidents, actually.  I\rquote d appointed one of the Chairman of the Health Authority, a very young Planning 
Officer, who was very bright, and he got a job in Saudi Arabia, and left, to my dismay.  And then came to see me one day, and said, \'93I\rquote ve got a very bright Saudi I think ought to do a Ph.D.\'94, so I interviewed him, and said, \'93
Okay, I think he\rquote s bright.  I\rquote ll take him on\'94.  Which I did.  And then he came and asked for another one, and I said, \'93No, no, one\rquote s enough\'94.  He said, \'93I\rquote ll tell you what.  Why don\rquote 
t you come out Riyadh, and have a look round, at our expense\'94.  So I went out, and one thing led to another, I had a number of Ph.D. students, but I also started doing consultancy work in Saudi Arabia, which \'85
 just as the Japanese and Sumatra was the area in the world, Saudi Arabia was an entirely different world.  And I did that for a number of years, a number of years.
