In Swansea, yes.  Yes.  And at any given time, we\rquote d have about 12.  I mean, I wouldn\rquote t be supervising them all, but, you know, I\rquote d recruit them, and then we sort of \'85 we\rquote 
d have to fit them to the interests of members of the staff, so we had a statistician, for example, ex-mathematician turned 
social statistician, who did a lot of statistical Ph.D.s., with huge bodies of data.  It worked very well.  And, in fact, it worked too well, because in the end, we simply had to say \'93No\'94
.  I also established, actually, a degree course, an undergraduate course in Diagnostic Radiography, in Saudi Arabia, which \'85 I would never do again if I had the chance.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10452181 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Why not, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10452181 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Horrendous problems!  Horrendous!  Well, it\rquote s a cultural thing, isn\rquote t it.  You \'85 we advertised, for the first course, we a
dvertised in the Arabic press for 25 places, and we had 6,000 applicants!  Which you reduce to about a thousand, without too much difficulty.  And then we reduced the 1000 to 300.  And then we gave them literacy and numeracy tests, and reduced them to 28,
 I think it was.  And when the first intake came in, there were 32, because four students had appeared on the admissions list, all the sons of \endash  because they\rquote re all men \endash  influential Saudis!  And so on, and so on.  So \'85
 but, I mean, I think nine graduated at the end of the third year, and they were good.  But it was so different from anything else I\rquote 
d experienced, I think it was very fortunate too.  And I still have friends there.  One of the students I had was a Saudi prince, Khalid, and very very good student.  Very good student.  And we still keep in touch with each other, so \'85
 ring each other up, and write each other letters, and things like this.  So that was fortunate, I think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10452181 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 And now you\rquote 
re retired in a Norfolk village, so what are your main interests now?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10452181 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Well, I\rquote 
m a keen gardener.  I\rquote ve become interested, in a very amateurish way, in computing, and \'85 at first, I was extremely Luddite, as far as I thought word processing wasn\rquote t a match to sitting down with a pen and writing!  But, ha
ving learned word processing, I then decided that I really ought to know a lot more about computing, so I spend \'85 not a lot of time, but I spend a certain amount of time on the computer, learning how to use it \'85 you know, \'85\'85\'85\'85
.. (INAUDIBLE \endash  071) like EXCEL and things like that, how to operate them, and voice recognition systems.  It\rquote s a game really, but it takes up a lot of time.  The extraordinary thing is that \'85 well, not so extraordinary, because it
\rquote s true of many people who have retired, that, in fact, I listen to a lot of music, that\rquote s another thing I do.  There\rquote 
s a whole list of things to do.  I mean, a big garden is a major enterprise which keeps me going right through the year, actually.  And \'85 um \'85 as I say, I listen to music, I read a certain amount.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10452181 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
You mentioned bell-ringing, too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid10452181 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Well, bell-ringing is only Thursday night and Sunday morning, unless there\rquote s a wedding or a funeral, and then I ring there.  I\rquote m not a good bell-ringer.  I\rquote m not.  I mean \'85
 the complications of different programmes are too difficult for me.  I don\rquote t have rope sight.  In order to be a bell-ringer, you have to be able to see where the other bell-ringers are ringing, so that you can fit in with them, and this is what
\rquote s called \'93rope sight\'94 and has to be developed, and I haven\rquote t developed it in the way that young boys, for example, do, they get it instinctively, and they know what Number 3 is doing, and if I\rquote m looking at Number 3, I\rquote 
m not sure what Number 5 is doing!  So I\rquote m a very modest bell-ringer, but it\rquote s enjoyable.  And then I play the clarinet.  I mean, it sounds like a very dull life, but it isn\rquote t.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
I thought you said that the bell-ringers were an interesting sort of network.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Oh yes.  Yes, there is a network, and \'85 erm \'85 I mean, for example, at the moment, Diss is having its bells re-hung, so the bell-ringers at Diss can\rquote 
t ring at Diss, so they come out, as it were, they spread out, so we will get bell-ringers from Diss coming.  And then Bressingham, they had trouble with their bells, I think, so they would come.  Or you find that \'85 two or three \'85
 I remember, in Kenninghall, three people went to live in Uist (?? \endash  098) or somewhere improbable like that, and left a gap, so in order to make up the gap, you call in people from outside.  And we try to ensure we ring every Sunday, so if we can
\rquote t make up \'85 you need five ringers, at least.  If we can\rquote t make up the five, we would ask a neighbouring Parish, whatever it is, to send a couple of people along, and then we would do the same for them.  So there is a network, and \'85
 pretty elderly \'85 pretty elderly.   There are no young people in Kenninghall at all.  There are in some villages, but it\rquote s a very difficult \'85 craft, or whatever it is, to persuade young people to und
ertake, because you need such enormous patience.  I mean, you only have practice for an hour and a half, once a week, and if you\rquote 
re learning, you might, in that hour and a half, get 15 minutes actual practice, which is an hour a month!  (LAUGHS)  So it takes a long time \'85 it takes a long time to get the minimum competency, and young people, normally, aren\rquote 
t prepared to do that, so \'85 I was a late developer, so \'85 but \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Do you miss being in Wales?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 No.  I don\rquote 
t.  I don\rquote t.  I mean, we had a house \'85 when we moved to East Anglia, we kept our Welsh house, and we used to go down there every summer.  And then we \'85
 it was a big house, we sold half of it, and kept the other half, and we used the other half as a sort of \'85 we used to go down for the whole of the summer, a couple of months, take the dog with us, and the cat, but then it\rquote s a long way, it
\rquote s a seven hour drive, or something like this, so you couldn\rquote t go down for a weekend, and we also wanted to buy a property in Reading, so we sold the Welsh house.  We miss it.  I mean, Jan misses it more than I do.  We miss it.  But, no, I
\rquote m low on nostalgia, I\rquote m afraid!  (LAUGHS)  Very low on nostalgia.  I\rquote d like to live by the sea.  We\rquote d both like to live by the sea, but apart from that \'85 I actually like li
ving in East Anglia.  I really like living in East Anglia, and it is so different from the rest of my life that I\rquote m fortunate in living in a sort of a \'85
 a vibrant village, that I actually enjoy it.  Go down every morning and get the paper, and I probably have four or five conversations during that visit.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 So you\rquote 
re still using your anthropological skills!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Well, no \'85 I don
\rquote t know!  I don\rquote t know.  There are some \'85 it is interesting, because there are some people in the village, and this goes back to community studies, I suppose, who have no contact with the village at all.  At all.  There\rquote 
s a couple who live a little bit further down, who have been in the village two years, and I don\rquote t know what their names are, and I don\rquote t think anyone else does, because they have no \'85
 the only contact they have is that they employ a local gardener, but apart from that, they live entirely enclosed.  And the Americans opposite, have no contact with the village at all, though I know this is policy, there is a yo
ung Air Force chap who works in Mildenhall, they don\rquote t participate in village life at all.  Very pleasant, I mean, I say \'93Good Morning\'94 to them, and things like that.  So there are people like that.  And when we lived in Brannerton (?? 
\endash  141), which was on the river, I mean, it was an isolated cottage, so, apart from one neighbour, you had to go half a mile to meet anyone else, and that made it much more difficult, and I don\rquote t think we\rquote 
d have had the same kind of life that we have here.  So I \'85 I\rquote m cultivating my garden!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
So, just to sum up.  I mean, looking back over your life, what do you think have been the least good things, and the best things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Well, the best thing, I think, is fairly easy.  I \'85 I \'85 I mean, nearly 20 \'85 well, it was 20 y
ears or so when I was in Swansea, when I was heavily involved in public life, and in academia, and still doing, for the first part of that, research.  And throughout, actually, that period, I always had six or seven research students, and six or seven Ph.
D. students is a good way of keeping in touch, because they would say, \'93I\rquote ve just found this book\'94, or whatever it was, or an article, and I\rquote 
d have to read it, to catch up with them!  So, as I say, I enjoyed the job enormously.  Sometimes very frustrating.  I think that was the best time.  I thought it was extremely fortunate.  Worst?  Well, it wasn\rquote 
t much fun being in the Army during the War, let me put it that way!  (LAUGHS)  I didn\rquote t like that very much, and some of it was exceptionally unpleasant, so \'85 and a lot of people I knew got killed, so \'85
 but as they say, it helped me to grow up.  I went in when I was 17, so \'85 you grow up very quickly.  I never think of it now.  Otherwise, I\rquote ve been very fortunate.  My health has been good, and \'85 I don\rquote t think I \'85 you know, I haven
\rquote t vegetated, I have \'85 I read a lot.  I haven\rquote t mentioned this.  I do read a lot.  We have a mobile library, which comes once a month, and I order lots of books, and my friend in the village, who is an avid reader, and he lends me lots of
 books, and I occasionally lend him books, and we talk about them, so we\rquote ve been reading, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The Different Lives of Iris Murdoch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 , for example, and so I\rquote m not stagnating in that sense.  But I don\rquote t mind a bit of stagnation, I\rquote m \'85 well, I\rquote m 77 now, so \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 PAUL:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 You\rquote 
ve done an awful lot.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 
Yes.  Yes.  Although I always remember, and it\rquote s something that\rquote s guided my life, actually, was \'85 once when I was in the Health Authority, I went to a hospital for the care of the elderly, and there was a woman there who
 had just celebrated her 100}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\super\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  birthday, I mean, this is one of the \'85 I\rquote 
ve got two apocryphal stories!  And I said to this woman, as everybody did, \'93What is the secret of living to 100?\'94  And she said, \'93Keep occupied\'94.  Right?  And I think that\rquote s \'85 that\rquote s the answer.  Keep occupied.  Because I
\rquote ve known lots of people, particularly civil servants, who retire at 60, and then just fade away, because they don\rquote t keep occupied.  But the other story, we mentioned Raymond Firth, wonderful story!  I went down to a s
eminar in LSE, and I arrived a bit early, and Raymond was coming into the Common Room, and he said, \'93It\rquote s rather a sad day, actually.  I\rquote ve just been talking to my father on the telephone, and he said it\rquote s his birthday, and he
\rquote s just told me that he\rquote s going to give up driving before his faculties start failing\'94.  And I said, \'93Oh yes.  How old is he, Raymond?\'94  \'93A hundred\'94, he said!  And Raymond, himself, lived, of course, until \'85 was it his \'85

