\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f42\fs22\insrsid2717339\charrsid4397916 W.M.:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid2717339   \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 Yes, that\rquote 
s right.  Yes.  So \'85 I thought, \'93Well, there you are!  Keep occupied and, you know, don\rquote t allow your faculties to fail\'94.  But I\rquote ve been fortunate.  I have been fortunate.  And I did try \'85 I haven\rquote 
t said this before, but I did, from time to time \'85 I mean, the thing about being Chairman of the Health Authority is its exciting.  Right?  It is exciting.  There\rquote 
s a lot going on, a lot of fire-fighting, so-called.  The chances of developing different kinds of services, I remember going to California to look at services for brain damage
d young adults, and being enormously impressed, and trying to introduce this, unsuccessfully, in Wales, and that kind of thing.  But it used to occur to me, from time to time, that although it was exciting, I was actually \'85 I haven\rquote 
t mentioned it, but I think increasingly losing touch with academia, which was imperceptible, and easy to do, but \'85 you know.  I mean, I read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535 The Sociological Review}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid12849482\charrsid7821535  now, and the monographs, far more assiduously than I did when I was a professor, because there was always something else to distract me.  And I think \'85
 although, at the same time, I\rquote m not sure I wanted simply to be a professor, and do nothing else in the outside world.  You know, I\rquote d have survived, and I\rquote d have updated my lectures and things like that, but I don\rquote t think I
\rquote m the sort of person that would be content with that.  I can remember travelling \'85 you talked about this, because Margaret also got involved, and I was travelling back from Paddington to Swansea, with Margaret, when I\rquote 
d just been appointed Chairman of the Health Authority, it was still a secret, and Margaret said, \'93Do you think they\rquote ve appointed the new Chairman of the Health Authority yet?\'94  And I said, \'93Yes, I think they have, Margaret\'94
, and thought, \'93She obviously has no idea, no idea who it is\'94.  And when she discovered, two or three days later, she said, \'93You\rquote d make an absolutely wonderful poker player, because I had no idea at all it was you!\'94  (LAUGHS)  So \'85

